[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Welcome to the course!"]
[Result "*"]

{ I am David Martinez, better known as El Divis! I have been playing the Dragon all my life and teaching for more than 15 years, coaching many strong players and this has given me a reputation for being very theoretical. I really enjoy working with machines and have always tried to surround myself with the best computers and engines to stay ahead of the players regarding opening preparation.  With that in mind, I was determined to get out a good Dragon course with a modern and innovative look at one of the most played lines in chess. It wasn't easy! But I devoted myself to offering everything I had analyzed, I have kept nothing back, so I have put aside my interest in the 'Divis' player to offer you all the lines of this ...Bh6 idea, plus more.  The players I train are not Dragon players, so I have put all these lines with novelties and innovation that I haven't used and I will show them to you. I've spent thousands of hours of work spread over the years and many, many hours more in making this Chessable course. I discarded some lines to choose well the ones I will show you in the course and added a few others after re-evaluating it again with the most updated engines.  Many positions are difficult for the engines and you have to put them to play against each other in certain difficult positions so that they change their mind about the first evaluations that gave a certain advantage to some side but that in practice was not reality. With the Dragon, the attacks radically change the evaluations by all the dynamics that we find in a lot of variations with sacrifices that will help you to better understand the game of chess.  These lines offer excellent practical possibilities and you will be able to surprise your opponents on more than one occasion and I hope that after publishing this course, the lines will be used and recognized in tournaments.  You should know that in this course we go out of the normal paths of the classic Dragon and with it you will get an advantage in certain positions and, with it, many chances to score some points.  My goal is for you to score more points! Now all of you are being trained with this course and I think it is a very good opening to play for a win with Black.  You'll see that in many variations we won't castle so there is no h4-h5 and mate.  Far from it! We'll be free to play without that concern and it will change the spirit of the position. It is true that the king in the center has other problems, but everything is covered in this course.  Editor's Note: Many variations in this course are very concrete, and the decision was made to often analyze them quite deeply into the variations with the aim of informing the student how the positions should be handled with perfect play. This means many positions end with an equal evaluation in a drawn ending, for example. This doesn't mean it's a drawish opening; far from it. Because the lines were so carefully analyzed and chosen, in practical play, you can be sure White will err far before they reach the end of the lines in this course.   Without further ado, enjoy this course very much and I hope you learn to value the positions beyond memorization. Welcome to the course! }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Dragon's Wing: 8.Qd2 - The Normal 10.Qf2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be3
{ The main move. } 6... Nc6
{ A more uncommon move, delaying the development of the Dragon bishop since after most of White's next moves, we have something different in mind for this piece. }
7. f3 h5
{ I found this idea while preparing for my 2018 Banter Blitz match against IM Paolo Ladrón de Guevara. At that time I was just looking for a line to surprise in blitz, but the deeper I went, the more excited I became about the variation!   Three years later, it is a pleasure for me to share with Chessable users all my analysis of the line. I'm not exaggerating if I tell you that behind the material you will see below the time spent can be counted in thousands of hours.   From here the material is practically virgin, with only 15 games played at the time of writing. So my task is to create practically the whole line in this position.   I gladly accept the challenge and welcome you to The Dragon Sicilian: Wing Attack. The analyses are made almost entirely with the help of the latest versions of Stockfish 12 on a computer with 48 core CPU and some even with more powerful computers!   I am, of course, aware of the evaluation given by the engine, sometimes pointing to a very wide advantage for White, but I ask the reader not to be carried away by these evaluations and to study the ideas I present here.   I am completely convinced that the variation is not only playable in practice, but it also gives much more winning chances than the usual variations. Without further ado, let's jump right in! }
8. Qd2
{ The automatic continuation in all the games played so far in this position except for one, in which White played  8.Bb5  . }
8... Nxd4 9. Bxd4 { The natural continuation. } 9... Bh6
{ The key point of this variation. We give White the choice between trading bishops or allowing our bishop to prevent them from castling long. }
10. Qf2 Qa5 11. Bb5+
{ White's most common attempt to prevent us from castling. } 11... Kf8
{ Black's king is safe on f8. The only real drawback is that the h8-rook will take some time to get into the game. }
12. Bc4 Be6 { The key idea! } 13. Bxe6 fxe6
{ This is the first contact we have with this original pawn structure. The king on f7 will not only feel safe around the pawns, but it will protect them too!   After having a look at the analysis of these lines, I'm sure that you will be willing to play this interesting pawn structure as Black. }
*

