8. Qd2
{ The automatic continuation in all the games played so far in this position except for one, in which White played  8.Bb5  . }
8... Nxd4 9. Bxd4 { The natural continuation. } 9... Bh6
{ The key point of this variation. We give White the choice between trading bishops or allowing our bishop to prevent them from castling long. }
10. Qf2 Qa5 { Looking for activity in the queenside. } 11. Bc4
{ This move doesn't prevent the development of our light-squared bishop. }
11... Be6 12. Bb3 Bxb3 13. cxb3
{ This capture is not troublesome because the c2-pawn usually suffers a lot in the semi-open file. }
13... O-O 14. a3 { The move b4 is scary, so we must meet it accurately. } 14...
Qa6 { Preventing White from castling short. } 15. b4 Qc4
{ This is our idea. We prevent issues that White wanted to create with b5. Next, we'll play ...Nd7 and bring a rook to c8 with a nice position for us. }
