1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Bc4
{ I had hardly paid attention to this move until this year when Dubov and Fedoseev used it in online tournaments. }
6... Bg7
{ In this case  6...Nc6  would be a serious mistake because White can play  7.Nxc6  and follow with e5. }
7. Be3
{ This is an order that Black players often 'forgive' and don't punish in the correct way. Here we will show complex and original lines that you will enjoy. }
7... Ng4 8. Bb5+
{ White's idea is to prevent us from castling, since  8...Bd7  is not possible because of the fact that the g4-knight is left unprotected. White can take it safely with  9.Qxg4  . }
8... Kf8 9. O-O Be5
{ The key move, creating weaknesses around White's castled king. From this point on it is necessary to know well the lines that we present here since a single mistake can cost the game. }
