8. Qd2
{ The automatic continuation in all the games played so far in this position except for one, in which White played  8.Bb5  . }
8... Nxd4 9. Bxd4 { The natural continuation. } 9... Bh6
{ The key point of this variation. We give White the choice between trading bishops or allowing our bishop to prevent them from castling long. }
10. Bb5+
{ This move was played by Shirov. The idea is to hinder our development. }
10... Bd7 11. Qd3
{ Removing the queen, but keeping it on the d-file to threaten Bxf6 followed by taking on d6. }
11... Bc6 { Defending the d6-pawn with the queen. } 12. Bxf6
{ White mustn't waste the opportunity to ruin our structure. } 12... exf6 13.
g3 { An interesting idea. White wants to play f4 and castle long. } 13... O-O
14. f4 f5 { Exploiting the fact that White's king is still in the center. } 15.
Bxc6 bxc6 16. O-O-O fxe4 17. Qxd6 Qa5
{ 17...Qe8  without giving the pawn, is also possible, but you know I have a passion for sacrificing pawns for initiative - I hope Maxime Vachier-Lagrave is proud of me! }
18. Qxc6
{ 18.Nxe4  ,  bringing the knight to the kingside is bad because it leaves the a2-pawn undefended. }
18... Bg7 { Threatening to bring a rook to c8 to liquidate on c3. } 19. Rd5
{ The precise move. } 19... Qb6 20. Qxb6 axb6 21. Kb1 Bxc3 22. bxc3 Rfd8
{ We have enough compensation and the endgame is equal. } *

