1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be3
{ The main move. } 6... Nc6
{ A more uncommon move, delaying the development of the Dragon bishop since after most of White's next moves, we have something different in mind for this piece. }
7. f3 h5
{ I found this idea while preparing for my 2018 Banter Blitz match against IM Paolo Ladrón de Guevara. At that time I was just looking for a line to surprise in blitz, but the deeper I went, the more excited I became about the variation!   Three years later, it is a pleasure for me to share with Chessable users all my analysis of the line. I'm not exaggerating if I tell you that behind the material you will see below the time spent can be counted in thousands of hours.   From here the material is practically virgin, with only 15 games played at the time of writing. So my task is to create practically the whole line in this position.   I gladly accept the challenge and welcome you to The Dragon Sicilian: Wing Attack. The analyses are made almost entirely with the help of the latest versions of Stockfish 12 on a computer with 48 core CPU and some even with more powerful computers!   I am, of course, aware of the evaluation given by the engine, sometimes pointing to a very wide advantage for White, but I ask the reader not to be carried away by these evaluations and to study the ideas I present here.   I am completely convinced that the variation is not only playable in practice, but it also gives much more winning chances than the usual variations. Without further ado, let's jump right in! }
8. Qd2
{ The automatic continuation in all the games played so far in this position except for one, in which White played  8.Bb5  . }
8... Nxd4 9. Bxd4 { The natural continuation. } 9... Bh6
{ The key point of this variation. We give White the choice between trading bishops or allowing our bishop to prevent them from castling long. }
10. f4
{ We can also meet this move with  10...O-O  ,  but I like to fight directly for the initiative. }
10... e5 11. Bb5+ Bd7
{ Stockfish insists on telling me to recommend  11...Ke7  , but I don't dare to make such a move! }
12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 { A really dynamic move. } 13. Be3 Ng4
{ Let's keep bothering White! } 14. Nd5
{ The bishop has no good squares to go to because the f4-pawn is attacked, so White takes advantage of this to place a strong knight in the center. }
14... Qa4
{ The key move. We forget everything to go to the center! We are threatening both the e4-pawn and to trade on e3 followed by taking on c2. }
15. b3 { Encouraging our queen to take on e4. } 15... Qxe4 16. O-O
{ Taking on e3 is impossible due to the fork on f6. } 16... Kf8
{ Now we can take on e3! } 17. Rae1
{ If  17.Bf2  we would play  17...Bxf4  with a good position despite giving up our beloved bishop for a little pawn. }
17... Nxe3 18. Rxe3 Qd4
{ We want to trade queens in order not to suffer due to the bad position of our king. Play could continue:   19.Qxd4  exd4  20.Re4  ,  we should still play accurately. If White gets the pawn back on their terms, we will be worse.  20...Rc8  ,  it is not clear if White is getting back the pawn while we have plenty of counterplay along the c-file.  21.Rf2  Bg7  ,  defense!    22.Rfe2  ,  White threatens the elegant Nc7 intending to mate us on e8.  22...h4  is an important move, gaining space on the kingside.  23.Nc7  Kg8  24.Ne8  d3  ,  looking to create counterplay.  25.cxd3  d5  ,  we want to get the d4-square for our bishop.  26.Re7  Bd4+  27.Kf1  Rc1+  28.Re1  Rc2  29.R1e2  Rc1+  and the game ends in a draw! }
