13. Bd4 { White fights for the control of the long diagonal. } 13... Nd7
{ Accepting the bishop trade.  13...a6  is slower, but it gives us good chances as well. }
14. Nb5 a6 { Forcing matters. } 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Nd4 Qb6
{ The queen is very well placed on b6 now because we will coordinate it with our pieces by playing ...Nc5-a4. }
17. Ka1
{ I point out this move because it's practically the only one against which ...Nc5 is not a good reply, so we have to be careful! }
17... Qc5 { 17...Nc5  is met with  18.Nf5+! } 18. h3 { Intending to play g4. }
18... h4
{ The typical move in this structure. We prevent g4 and we should take into account that White is going to prove that our h-pawn is a weakness. }
19. Qf2 Rh8 20. f4 { Again going for the f5 pawn break. } 20... Nb8
{ Rerouting the knight and, at the same time, we give the d7-square to our bishop. The position is under our control. }
