8. Qd2
{ The automatic continuation in all the games played so far in this position except for one, in which White played  8.Bb5  . }
8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4
{ The only point of this move is that it prevents ...Bh6. In return, White will soon have to lose another tempo with the queen. }
9... Bg7 10. O-O-O O-O
{ Threatening ...Ng4, so White's queen should move away. } 11. Qd2
{ The move that all our opponents are likely to make. } 11... Be6
{ We should keep in mind the ...Be6, ...Rc8, ...Qa5 and ...Nd7 configuration, to point our pieces to the queenside. }
12. Kb1
{ A useful move that prevents ...Qa5 as White will meet it with Nd5. The key to that line is that ...Qxd2 wouldn't be check, so the intermediate move Nxe7+ wins material. }
12... Rc8
{ Another option that's worth investigating is  12...a6  with the idea of ...b5. }
13. h3 { Intending to play g4, but ignroring Black's threats. } 13... Rxc3
{ A typical exchange sacrifice which is more than justified in this position, as the bishop on e3 falls along the way. }
14. Qxc3
{ Only move.  14.bxc3  loses on the spot:  14...Nxe4!  15.fxe4  Qa5  and nobody can save White's king! }
14... Nd5 15. Qa3 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 Qa5
{ The queen coordinates perfectly with the bishops. } 17. a3
{ 17.Qa3  is the only alternative. However, after trading on a3, Black will have a good endgame. Next, we can play moves such as ...Rc8 and attack White's queenside pawns or stop White's intentions on the kingside by putting a bishop on e5. }
17... b5 { Going for the ...b4 pawn break. } 18. c3
{ Stopping ...b4 but weakening the light squares around the king. } 18... Qa4
{ Trying to exploit the weakened light-squares and, at the same time, freeing the way of the a-pawn to push ...b4 next. }
19. Be2
{ The idea of this move is to meet  19...Qb3  with the exchange sacrifice  20.Rd5  . }
19... a5 { We keep on bringing pieces to the attack. } 20. Rd5
{ The best defense. } 20... Bxd5 21. exd5 b4 22. cxb4 axb4 23. Bd1
{ The only option to try to keep the queenside closed. } 23... Qb5 24. a4 Qxd5
{ Black is a pawn up. However, the presence of opposite-colored bishops on the board gives White some hope to end the game in a draw. }
