{ The automatic continuation in all the games played so far in this position except for one, in which White played  8.Bb5  . }
8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4
{ The only point of this move is that it prevents ...Bh6. In return, White will soon have to lose another tempo with the queen. }
9... Bg7 10. Bc4 { White preempts the development of our bishop on e6. } 10...
O-O 11. Qd2 a6
{ Opting for this plan with which we'll win a tempo on White's c4-bishop. } 12.
O-O-O b5 13. Bb3 { 13.Bd5  Rb8  is not a problem. } 13... Bd7
{ Defending the b5-pawn in order to play ...a5. } 14. Nd5
{ Removing our knight from the board to try to weaken our kingside. } 14...
Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Rc8 { This rook loves the c-file! } 16. h4
{ Intending to play Bh6 and g4. } 16... b4
{ We calmly prepare our counterplay. } 17. Bh6 Qb6
{ Time to bring the queen into life.  17...Qc7  is also a good option. } 18. g4
{ Most of the time our opponents will attack us without worrying about other things. In any case, our reaction will be the same. }
18... e6 { Doesn't this sound familiar to you? } 19. Bb3 a5 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21.
Qxd6 Qxd6
{ 21...Qe3+  22.Kb1  a4  is also a good option, so just choose the one of your preference! }
22. Rxd6 Bb5 { Threatening both ...a4 and ...Be2. } *

