O-O 11. Qd2 a6
{ Opting for this plan with which we'll win a tempo on White's c4-bishop. } 12.
a4 { Preventing ...b5 but cutting off the possibility of castling long. } 12...
Qc7 13. Bb3 Be6 { When there's no knight on d4, this move is solid. } 14. Bxe6
fxe6
{ Although our pawn structure is ugly, it's not easy to attack. Our idea is to bring our knight to d7 and a rook to c8. }
15. Ne2 Nd7
{ The less forcing option, keeping pieces on the board and following the aforementioned plan. When the knight moves from f6, the bishop already attacks b2. }
16. Nd4 { On  16.c3  we would continue  16...Ne5  . } 16... Rfc8 17. Rc1
{ Overprotecting c2 to threaten the pawn on e6. } 17... e5
{ Reaching a typical stucture of this variation, which gives dynamism to our position and, at the same time, protects our castling, although it may not seem like doing so. }
18. Ne2 { Dreaming about the idea of bringing the knight to d5. } 18... Qc6
{ Intending to play ...b5. } 19. Nc3 e6 { Preventing the knight jump to e6. }
20. a5 { 20.Rd1  is still premature because of  20...Nb6! } 20... b6
{ We want to get the b6-square for our knight! } 21. Rd1 Bf8 22. Bh6
{ The most critical move, trying to take on d6. Against ...Be7, White would insist on Bg5, so I recommend another alternative. }
22... bxa5 23. Bxf8 Nxf8 24. Qxd6 Qb7
{ With a very complex position, strategically speaking, given our so interesting pawn structure. However, due to the fact that our rooks are better placed, we have enough dynamism to be happy here. }
