8. Be2
{ White reacts against our ...h5 push by preparing to castle short and later on dream with an f5 break. }
8... e5
{ The move that convinced me at the time that this variation was playable. I think that after ...Bg7 we play an inferior version of a standard Dragon. }
9. Nb3 Be6 10. O-O h4
{ I like this way of playing to fight from now on for the f4-square. It should be noted that  10...d5  is not possible because after exchanging on d5 White will play Qe1, creating some problems. }
11. h3 { The eternal dilemma of whether or not to allow Black to play ...h3. }
11... Nh5 { Controlling the key squares on the kingside. } 12. Qd2 Be7
{ No hurry. We aim to castle and then seize the key squares. } 13. Nd5 Ng3 14.
Rfe1 { An important move that keeps the e2-bishop defended. } 14... Bxd5 15.
exd5 Nb8 16. Na5 Qc7 17. Qb4 { This is White's annoying idea. } 17... Nxe2+ 18.
Rxe2 b6 19. Nc4 O-O
{ This position reminds me of those in the Sveshnikov that Carlsen played against Caruana in the World Championship Match in 2018. White seizes the initiative on the queenside, but Black reacts on the kingside.   The knight on d7 can jump to c5 or find a longer route via f6-h5. In addition, we'll play ...f5 gaining space, threatening some pawn breaks, and even pushing ...g5-g4 is some positions. In short, a position with a lot of life! }
