11... Nh5 { Controlling the key squares on the kingside. } 12. Qd2 Be7
{ No hurry. We aim to castle and then seize the key squares. } 13. Nd5 Ng3 14.
Rfe1 { An important move that keeps the e2-bishop defended. } 14... Bxd5 15.
exd5 Nb8 16. Na5 Qc7 17. Bb5+ Nd7 18. Qc3
{ This is another far-fetched machine idea trying to squeeze us on the queenside. }
18... Qxc3 19. bxc3 a6 { Inviting White to give up the bishop pair advantage. }
20. Bd3 { I don't think many of our opponents will grant our wish. } 20... b6
21. Nc6 Bf6
{ The position could be somewhat cramped for us, but after castling and putting the rooks on their best squares, we'll only have one weakness - the b6-pawn. Let's see what happens if White grabs it. }
22. Rab1 O-O 23. Bxb6 Nxb6 24. Rxb6 Bg5
{ We want to play ...Rfe8, ...f5 and ...e4. I think that despite being a pawn down, our position is easier to play! Or is that e-pawn not worth more than White's c-pawns? }
