{ Intending to play ...Bg4, grabbing the e5-pawn soon. At the same time, we push our passed pawn up the board! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Dragon's Wing: The Tame 8.Be2"]
[Black "The Tame 8.Be2: 9.Nxc6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be3
{ The main move. } 6... Nc6
{ A more uncommon move, delaying the development of the Dragon bishop since after most of White's next moves, we have something different in mind for this piece. }
7. f3 h5
{ I found this idea while preparing for my 2018 Banter Blitz match against IM Paolo Ladrón de Guevara. At that time I was just looking for a line to surprise in blitz, but the deeper I went, the more excited I became about the variation!   Three years later, it is a pleasure for me to share with Chessable users all my analysis of the line. I'm not exaggerating if I tell you that behind the material you will see below the time spent can be counted in thousands of hours.   From here the material is practically virgin, with only 15 games played at the time of writing. So my task is to create practically the whole line in this position.   I gladly accept the challenge and welcome you to The Dragon Sicilian: Wing Attack. The analyses are made almost entirely with the help of the latest versions of Stockfish 12 on a computer with 48 core CPU and some even with more powerful computers!   I am, of course, aware of the evaluation given by the engine, sometimes pointing to a very wide advantage for White, but I ask the reader not to be carried away by these evaluations and to study the ideas I present here.   I am completely convinced that the variation is not only playable in practice, but it also gives much more winning chances than the usual variations. Without further ado, let's jump right in! }
8. Be2
{ White reacts against our ...h5 push by preparing to castle short and later on dream with an f5 break. }
8... e5
{ The move that convinced me at the time that this variation was playable. I think that after ...Bg7 we play an inferior version of a standard Dragon. }
9. Nxc6
{ Engines recommend this move to punish our ...e5 push, But from a human point of view, does anyone think this can be any good? Time to prove the machines wrong! }
9... bxc6 10. Qd2 { A more direct approach, targetting d6. } 10... Be6 11.
O-O-O Be7
{ There is no shame for this bishop to develop on e7 to defend the d6-pawn. }
12. Bg5 O-O 13. Bxf6 { White's greedy -and wrong- option. } 13... Bxf6 14. Qxd6
Qa5 15. Qxc6
{ This is the kind of position that has to make us smile as Banter Blitz Dragon players. It's true that our dark-squared bishop hardly plays; however, with the b- and c-files available to attack and good coordination with the queen and bishop, it's time to make the white king suffer! }
15... Rab8 16. Rd5 { There's no good defense but this isn't a bad attempt! }
16... Bxd5 17. Nxd5
{ Taking with the pawn is not possible due to ...Bg5 and ...Rfc8, winning material. }
17... Qxa2 18. Qxf6 Qa1+ 19. Kd2 Qxh1 20. Qxe5 Rfd8
{ We're two exchanges up and a very active queen, which is going to put White in so much trouble. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Dragon's Wing: 8.Bc4 / 12.Kb1 Mainline"]
[Black "12.Kb1 Mainline: 14.h3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be3
{ The main move. } 6... Nc6
{ A more uncommon move, delaying the development of the Dragon bishop since after most of White's next moves, we have something different in mind for this piece. }
7. f3 h5
{ I found this idea while preparing for my 2018 Banter Blitz match against IM Paolo Ladrón de Guevara. At that time I was just looking for a line to surprise in blitz, but the deeper I went, the more excited I became about the variation!   Three years later, it is a pleasure for me to share with Chessable users all my analysis of the line. I'm not exaggerating if I tell you that behind the material you will see below the time spent can be counted in thousands of hours.   From here the material is practically virgin, with only 15 games played at the time of writing. So my task is to create practically the whole line in this position.   I gladly accept the challenge and welcome you to The Dragon Sicilian: Wing Attack. The analyses are made almost entirely with the help of the latest versions of Stockfish 12 on a computer with 48 core CPU and some even with more powerful computers!   I am, of course, aware of the evaluation given by the engine, sometimes pointing to a very wide advantage for White, but I ask the reader not to be carried away by these evaluations and to study the ideas I present here.   I am completely convinced that the variation is not only playable in practice, but it also gives much more winning chances than the usual variations. Without further ado, let's jump right in! }
8. Bc4
{ Dodging Black's ideas but, at the same time, accepting the challenge of playing the most aggressive lines against the Dragon. In my original analysis, I have dozens of different possibilities to play against this line but, in the end, I've chosen to play as in the classical line, but with ...h5 and delaying castling.   The idea has the advantage that it makes White's attack on the kingside slower but, on the other hand, the attacks in the center will be more dangerous and we're giving them an immediate break point. }
8... Bd7 9. Qd2 Bg7 10. O-O-O Ne5
{ I was very close to recommending lines with  10...Na5  which work very, very well against  11.Bb3  , which is almost the most played move here. However, it's not as effective against  11.Bd3  or  11.Be2  so I rather recommend the old -but reliable- move. }
11. Bb3 Rc8
{ We have reached the main line of the variation. White has different options, mainly depending on whether they prefer to play in the center or break with g4. }
12. Kb1
{ The most usual move. White improves the king and waits to see our reaction. }
12... Nc4 13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. h3 h4
{ We don't want to allow g4 and we'll also take advantage of the h5-square both for the knight -as we have seen other times- and to lift the rook to the fourth rank. }
15. Rhe1
{ Once White cannot manage to create problems on the kingside, they try in the center. }
15... Rh5 { Our rook can play along the fourth rank. } 16. Nde2
{ Leaving the d4-square for the bishop while preparing the Nf4-d5 maneuver. }
16... Kf8 { Slightly improving the king's position. } 17. Bd4 b5
{ Time to stop the subtle improvements and go for the attack. } 18. b3 Rxd4 19.
Nxd4 b4 20. Nce2 Rc5
{ 20...a5  was also possible but this  option is more dynamic. White can take the pawn but must be careful with the d4-knight! }
21. Qxb4 a5 22. Qd2
{ 22.Qa3  is another try. This move is interesting because there is a powerful tactical shot:  22...e5  23.Ne6+  .  This is the idea.  23...fxe6  24.Rxd6  and now White's idea is clear. The rook cannot move.  24...Qc7  25.Red1  ,  Rxd7 is unstoppable.  25...Kf7  26.Rxd7+  Nxd7  27.Rxd7+  Qxd7  28.Qxc5  Qd1+  29.Nc1  Bh6  30.Qa3  Qg1  ,  taking on g2 and h3. White will have drawing chances but not more than that.  31.c4  Qxg2  32.Qxa5  Qxh3  33.Qc7+  Kf6  34.Qd8+  Kf7  and the game ends in a draw by perpetual check. }
22... e5
{ The knight has no squares so they must create an escape. Play could continue as follows:   23.b4  axb4  24.Nb3  Rc6  25.Qxb4  , when  White is an exchange and a pawn up but we have good attacking ideas on the queenside.  25...Rb6  26.Qd2  Be6  followed by ...Qb8 and improve the knight by bringing it to the c5-square. I leave you here with a very nice position to play, don't waste it! }
*

