11. Bb3 Rc8
{ We have reached the main line of the variation. White has different options, mainly depending on whether they prefer to play in the center or break with g4. }
12. Kb1
{ The most usual move. White improves the king and waits to see our reaction. }
12... Nc4 13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. h3 h4
{ We don't want to allow g4 and we'll also take advantage of the h5-square both for the knight -as we have seen other times- and to lift the rook to the fourth rank. }
15. Rhe1
{ Once White cannot manage to create problems on the kingside, they try in the center. }
15... Rh5 { Our rook can play along the fourth rank. } 16. f4
{ Supporting the e5 break but leaving the e4-pawn weak. } 16... Qc8
{ Boosting the sacrifice on c3. How much damage would the knight do by entering on e4 and c3! }
17. e5
{ This move is not scary at all as our rook came to h5 in order to prevent these kinds of moves. }
17... dxe5 18. fxe5 Rxe5 19. Bh6 Rxe1 20. Rxe1 Bh8
{ Our bishop is much better than our opponent's and also prevents the white queen to get into our position through h6. }
