by bringing the rook to e8.  24...Nd5  24.e6  ,  trying to ruin our castling structure.  24...Bxd4  25.Nxd4  Nxc3+  26.Qxc3  Bd5  and here's our counterpunch.  27.exf7  Bxa2+  28.Kxa2  Qd5+  29.Nb3  axb3+  30.Qxb3  Ra8+  31.Kb1  Qxb3  32.cxb3  Kxf7  with a likely draw.  23...Qc7  23.e5  Ne8  ,  White is certainly squeezing us. Hold on!  24.Ne4   24.e6  creates weaknesses in our camp but, moreover, it partially closes the position.  25...f5  25.Rg1  Qb7  ,  preventing g4 for the moment, at least.  26.Bxg7+  Nxg7  27.Nd4  b4  28.axb4  Qxb4  29.Nxc6  Rxc6  30.Nd5  Qc4  31.Qd2  ,  keeping the queens on the board is White's only option to try to punish us.  31...Rh7  ,  when we'll follow up with moves such as ...Nh5 or ...Nxe6 if White doesn't defend the pawn!  25...dxe5  25.fxe5  Kg8  and our position is still solid. Now we improve the position of our king.  26.Bc3  ,  White also improves their position. The bishop frees the d-file and leaves open the possibility of a knight jumping to d4.  27...Qb7  27.Neg5  e6  .  Our bishop on d5 will strengthen our position and we can also play ...Bf8 with the idea of going ...b4 next. }
