8. Bc4
{ Dodging Black's ideas but, at the same time, accepting the challenge of playing the most aggressive lines against the Dragon. In my original analysis, I have dozens of different possibilities to play against this line but, in the end, I've chosen to play as in the classical line, but with ...h5 and delaying castling.   The idea has the advantage that it makes White's attack on the kingside slower but, on the other hand, the attacks in the center will be more dangerous and we're giving them an immediate break point. }
8... Bd7 9. Qd2 Bg7 10. O-O-O Ne5
{ I was very close to recommending lines with  10...Na5  which work very, very well against  11.Bb3  , which is almost the most played move here. However, it's not as effective against  11.Bd3  or  11.Be2  so I rather recommend the old -but reliable- move. }
11. Bb3 Rc8
{ We have reached the main line of the variation. White has different options, mainly depending on whether they prefer to play in the center or break with g4. }
12. Kb1
{ The most usual move. White improves the king and waits to see our reaction. }
12... Nc4 13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. Nde2
{ The knight moves away, making room for the bishop and with the idea of targeting the d5-square in the future. }
14... b5 15. Bd4 Qb8 { Preventing e5. } 16. Nd5 e5
{ The best way to fight against White's initiative. } 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Be3
{ The engine 'likes' this move at first but, as we go deeper, it's not as good as it seems. }
18... Be7 19. Nc3
{ The knight wants to dominate the whole board from d5, so we shouldn't allow it to get there. }
19... Be6 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. Qxd5 O-O
{ I understand that it may seem, at first glance, that our position is inferior; but in reality, we're in a 'Pelikan' position where we have counterplay on the c-file and no obvious weaknesses apart from d6. Let's play a little with Stockfish to show that it is not so serious:   22.b3  ,  kicking the rook away so White can play f4. In case of doing it directly, we would have the reply ...Qa8 to take on e4 next.  22...Rc7  23.Rhf1  Qb7  ,  White's queen is definitely good, let's trade it!  24.f4  exf4  25.Bxf4  Re8  26.Rfe1  Qc6  and around here Stockfish is realizing that the position is balanced. We will bring the bishop to f8 in order to put pressure on e4, reminding White that each side has a weakness in the center and, besides, the pawn on c2 can't be happy either! }
