18. Nd5
{ An attempt to simplify the position, dreaming about converting the material advantage at some point. }
18... Nxd5 19. Qxd5 Rc8
{ We're in no hurry because our compensation is positional. Then we can try to activate the queen through the dark squares or expand on the queenside. On White's side, the strongest plan is to bring the knight to d5 and then try to attack us on the kingside. Let's look at one possibility:   20.Nf4  Qc7  21.Qd2  e6  is a move that may seem a bit conflictive because, in fact, it avoids the jump to d5, but the pawn on d6 is very weak. The idea is that it's not easy to take advantage of it because of the pressure we apply on c2 and the constant threat of entering via the dark squares of White's castling. In addition, as we will see below, we'll have ...d5 ideas.    22.h4  ,  intending to continue with g4.  22...a5  23.g4  hxg4  24.h5  d5  ,  the right moment. We threaten ...Qe5 so White has one only reply now.  25.Nd3  dxe4  26.fxe4  Bc6  27.h6  Bf8  .  White has managed to force our bishop off the long diagonal, but in return, our king will be safe on the h-file. Soon we will be able to play ...Kh7 and then ...a4 with greater attacking chances than our opponent. }
