8. Bc4
{ Dodging Black's ideas but, at the same time, accepting the challenge of playing the most aggressive lines against the Dragon. In my original analysis, I have dozens of different possibilities to play against this line but, in the end, I've chosen to play as in the classical line, but with ...h5 and delaying castling.   The idea has the advantage that it makes White's attack on the kingside slower but, on the other hand, the attacks in the center will be more dangerous and we're giving them an immediate break point. }
8... Bd7 9. Qd2 Bg7 10. O-O-O Ne5
{ I was very close to recommending lines with  10...Na5  which work very, very well against  11.Bb3  , which is almost the most played move here. However, it's not as effective against  11.Bd3  or  11.Be2  so I rather recommend the old -but reliable- move. }
11. Bb3 Rc8
{ We have reached the main line of the variation. White has different options, mainly depending on whether they prefer to play in the center or break with g4. }
12. Kb1
{ The most usual move. White improves the king and waits to see our reaction. }
12... Nc4 13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. Qd3
{ This move was played by Stockfish against Lc0 and the game was very exciting! }
14... Qc8 15. Nb3 { 15.Rhe1  O-O  would transpose to 14.Rhe1. } 15... O-O 16.
h3 b5
{ 16...h4  is the standard move, but Lc0 assessed correctly that the move g4 is not a big issue at the moment. }
17. Na5 { A precise move that fearlessly aims to take on b5. } 17... Rc7
{ Sacrificing the exchange is an interesting option because, without open files to work on, the rooks will have a hard time showing their strength. }
18. Nxb5 { Very few human players would dare to play this way. } 18... Bxb5 19.
Qxb5 Qa8
{ The queen gets out of the way to leave room for Black's rook and, at the same time, from a8 supports the ...d5 break. Let's see how play could continue:   20.Bd4  ,  trying to prevent the bishop on g7 from causing more damage. Retreating to d3 with the queen is not a good option because of ...Nd7 and the knight would get to c5 winning a tempo.  20...e5  ,  a fight to the death for the initiative. This move is followed by ...d5 against all of White's bishop retreats.  21.Bf2  is a nice retreat intending to play Bg3 to continue attacking the e5-pawn.  21...d5  22.Bg3   22.Bh4  ,  threatening to take on f6 and d5. This is a move we have to be prepared against.  After  22...Rb8  23.Qe2  ,  White might think that the queen on a4 is better placed but after ...d4 and ...Nd7, it will be in danger!  23...d4  changes the nature of the position since our bishop will not be able to collaborate with the queenside, at least not for a long time.  24.g4  with the idea of following with Bxf6 and gxh5.  24...Rb6  and now it's the rook that moves out of the way to make room for the queen.  25.Bxf6  Bxf6  26.gxh5  Qb8  27.Nb3  a5  28.a4  Bg5  ,  activating the bishop to bring it to e3 or f4. White, despite the two extra pawns, has trouble finding a plan while we'll go for the pawn on a4, usually by playing ...Qe8.  22...Rfc8  ,  no time to think about defending the e5-pawn! White must accept the material offer.  23.Bxe5  Rxc2  24.exd5  Rxg2  ,  taking a pawn but also aiming to play ...Rcc2. Black has good compensation for the pawn.  Because of its relevance, let's take a look at the continuation of the game between Stockfish and Lc0.  25.Rh2  ,  trading the active rook seems to be a good idea.  25...Rxh2  26.Bxh2  Re8  .  Surgeon's precision. Black can enter on e3 or play ...Qd8: maximum piece activity!  27.Qc6  Qd8  28.Nc4  Nd7  ,  freeing the long diagonal so the bishop can do its job there.  29.Qc7  Qe7  30.Rc1  Kh7  31.Bg3  with the idea of playing Be1 and bringing it to c3. }
