8. Bc4
{ Dodging Black's ideas but, at the same time, accepting the challenge of playing the most aggressive lines against the Dragon. In my original analysis, I have dozens of different possibilities to play against this line but, in the end, I've chosen to play as in the classical line, but with ...h5 and delaying castling.   The idea has the advantage that it makes White's attack on the kingside slower but, on the other hand, the attacks in the center will be more dangerous and we're giving them an immediate break point. }
8... Bd7 9. Qd2 Bg7 10. O-O-O Ne5
{ I was very close to recommending lines with  10...Na5  which work very, very well against  11.Bb3  , which is almost the most played move here. However, it's not as effective against  11.Bd3  or  11.Be2  so I rather recommend the old -but reliable- move. }
11. Bb3 Rc8
{ We have reached the main line of the variation. White has different options, mainly depending on whether they prefer to play in the center or break with g4. }
12. Kb1
{ The most usual move. White improves the king and waits to see our reaction. }
12... Nc4 13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. Rhe1
{ With the idea of following with Bg5 and break in the center. } 14... O-O
{ As so often, once we are out of danger on the kingside, we castle both to protect our king and to bring the rook into the game. }
15. Qd3 Qc8 16. h3 h4
{ This time we're not going to let them play g4. In addition, we win the h5-square for the knight. }
17. Nb3 { Making way for the bishop. } 17... Be6 18. Bd4 Re8
{ A useful waiting move to meet f4 with ...b5. We don't play ...a6 because b6 is weak and the knight on c3 will take advantage of it. }
19. f4 b5
{ The race has begun. Definitely chances for both sides. Let's see some possible continuations:   20.g4  b4  21.Nb5  .  Had Black played ...a6, White would have played Na4 and we would be in trouble.   21.Ne2  Rc7  ,  intending to enter on c4.  22.Nd2  Bd7  ,  pulling our bishop back to prepare the counterpunch.  23.f5  e5  24.fxe6  Bxe6  25.Rf1  .  This move will be met brilliantly.  25...Nxe4  26.Nxe4  Bc4  27.Qf3  Bxe2  28.Qxe2  d5  29.Bxg7  Rxe4  30.Qf3  Kxg7  31.Qf6+  Kg8  32.Rxd5  Re8  ,  reaching an even position.  21...a6  22.Bxf6  Bxf6  23.N5d4  and we've reached an interesting position where White has the initiative because they're breaking on f5 very soon.   23.e5  is a good try to fight for the initiative.  23...dxe5  24.Bxe5  Rc5  25.Nd4  Rd8  with the idea of ...Ba4. We have the files under our control and we have good attacking chances on the queenside.  23...Rc7  ,  giving the c4-square for the bishop.  24.Nxe6  Qxe6  25.Qxa6  and this conflictive pawn will be important if White manages, someday, to think of mobilizing the queenside, which is something still far away from being real!  After  25...Bg7  26.e5  Qc8  27.Qxc8  Rexc8  ,  Black is a pawn down. However, the pawn on b4 serves as a wedge to keep the queenside immobile and b2 under permanent attack. Our next move can be ...Rc4, to attack f4 and protect b4. }
