{ We have a painfully simple plan of steamrolling White down the c-file. Only with concrete play can White prevent it. Let's see some sample lines:   A.  19.e5  is the pawn break that we always have to calculate.  19...Ne8  20.exd6  Nxd6  21.Bxg7  Nf5  22.Qg5  Nxg7  23.g4  .  They're coming for us; maximum accuracy, please!  23...Rc6  24.Nd4   24.gxh5  Nxh5  25.Nd4  Rb6  26.Rxe6  and White can't take with the knight on e6 due to ...Qxc3.  26...Rxb2+  27.Kxb2  Qxc3+  28.Kb1  fxe6  29.Qxg6+  Ng7  .  Has the blowing storm stopped? Not yet!  30.Rg1  Qxd4  31.Qxe6+  Kh7  32.Rxg7+  Kxg7  33.Qxc8  Qd1+  34.Kb2  Qxf3  .  The storm has subsided and the game should end in a draw.  24...Rb6  25.Rd3  ,  defending against the ...Qxc3 threat.  25...Rd8  ,  renewing the threat. We want to play ...Rxd4 to take on c3 next.  26.b3  Rbd6  27.Red1  Qb6  ,  we have good coordination and the kingside defended in an original way. The position is indeed playable for both sides.   B.  19.g4  will be met with a subtle retreat.  19...Rc6  ,  threatening ...Bxb3 followed by ...e5 and we'll end up trapping the a7-bishop by playing ...b6. The best move would be Qd2, which we would answer with ...b5, but let's see in depth what would happen if White omits our threat:    20.gxh5  Bxb3  21.axb3  e5  22.Ba7  b6  23.hxg6  Qxa7  24.gxf7+  Qxf7  25.Rg1  .  White has two pawns to compensate for the piece. However, as long as we have an eye for the knight jump to d5, we can aim to improve our position little by little.  25...Kh7  ,  the idea is playing ...Bh6 at some point.  26.Qg5  ,  the queen heads to f5.  26...b5  ,  threatening ...b4 to be able to penetrate on c2.  27.Rg2  b4  28.Nd5  Nxd5  29.exd5  Bh6  .  The position is complex, but we have better chances than our opponent to play for a win. }
