15. g5
{ 15.Kb1  Bc6  ,  freeing the d7-square for the knight.  16.Nde2  Nd7  17.Bd4  is White's usual plan to exchange bishops.  17...Be5  −  if White wants to trade our bishop, let's allow it, but in exchange for improving our knight's position! }
15... Nh7 16. Kb1
{ White continues improving their position before taking further action.   A.  16.Nde2  ,  intending to play Bd4.  16...a5  ,  trying to create weaknesses on the queenside. After  17.Kb1  a4  ,  we keep on pushing the a-pawn.  18.a3  O-O  19.Bd4   19.Nd5  Rfe8  ,  protecting e7. Against Nb6 we can play ...Qb5.  20.Bd4  Bxd4  21.Nxd4  Qc5  and now we must prevent Nb6.  22.f4  e5  23.Ne2  exf4  24.Nexf4  Rxe4  25.Nxh5  − they come with everything they have!  25...gxh5  26.Nf6+  Nxf6  27.gxf6  ,  White has sacrificed a piece but now threatens Qh6.  27...Kh7  28.Qg2  ,  threatening mate on g7 and the e4-rook!  Following  28...Qxc2+  29.Qxc2  Rxc2  30.Kxc2  Bf5  ,  we have a pawn for the exchange. However, since White has almost as many weaknesses as pawns, we'll have good compensation for the material.  19...e5  20.Be3  Be6  ,  all or nothing.  21.Qxd6   21.Nc1  is the slow option. White improves the knight's position.  21...f5  22.gxf6  Rxf6  ,  attacking on f3.  23.Qg2  Rcf8  ,  we keep on insisting.  24.Rhf1  b5  and now on the queenside. Although we have an ugly structure, the dynamics of our position compensate for the weaknesses. Let's see a possible continuation.  25.Nd5  Bxd5  26.Rxd5  b4  ,  coordinating the attack along the b- and f-files.  21...f6  22.gxf6  Rxf6  ,  attacking the f3-pawn and threatening ...Bxh3. Both threats cannot be parried at the same time.  23.Ng1  is a new engine finesse that aims to defend f3; there's no other way to do this!  23...Bxh3  24.Qd5+  Be6  with a complex game.   B.  16.f4  insists on attacking our king.  16...O-O  17.Kb1  Rfe8  ,  intending to play ...e5 and take with the rook.  18.Qf2  e5  19.fxe5  Rxe5  20.Nf3  Ra5  ,  threatening ...Bxc3 and the entrance on a2.  21.Bd4  Nxg5  ,  one pawn has fallen, but White reacts.  22.Bxg7  Kxg7  23.Rxd6  and we could take on e4 to enter on a2 next, but I prefer another option.  23...Nxf3  24.Rxd7  Qe6  , hitting the rook and threatening  ...Rxc3  followed by penetrating on  a2  .  25.Rd5  Rxd5  26.exd5  Qf5  and we have a nice position. }
16... O-O { As White won't attack us yet, this is a good moment to castle. }
17. Nde2 { White wants to play Bd4. } 17... Be6 18. Bd4 b5
{ Threatening ...b4. } 19. b3
{ After  19.Bxg7  Kxg7  20.b3  Qc5  ,  the queen is well placed on c5.  21.f4  Rfe8  ,  protecting on e7 and preempting the imminent Nd5.  22.Nd5  a5  with the idea of ...a4. White is getting closer to our king, so this is a pure Dragon-style position.  23.f5  gxf5  24.Nef4  fxe4  ,  taking at this point on h5 isn't dangerous for us because after ...Kh8 we threaten to take on d5.  25.Qe2  Bf5  ,  defending on e4 and, at the same time, reminding White to take care of the c2-pawn!  26.Nxh5+  Kh8  27.h4  ,  White's attack is slow but very dangerous. Since we can't do anything, let's continue with our counterattack!  27...e6  28.Ne3  a4  with the idea of ...Qc3. The position is double-edged. }
19... Qb4 20. Kb2 { A good defensive move intending to go a3. } 20... Rc7
{ We want to play ...Rfc8. } 21. a3
{ 21.f4  Rfc8  will end up transposing because White will have to play a3 anyway to continue improving the position. }
21... Qa5 22. Bxg7 { 22.f4  first will simply transpose. } 22... Kxg7 23. f4
Rfc8 { We have good counterplay along the c-file. } 24. Qd4+
{ 24.Qd3  Kg8  ,  preempting White's check on d4 to be able to play ...b4.  25.f5  gxf5  26.exf5  b4  27.axb4  Qxf5  with a somewhat cramped -but close to even- endgame.  28.Nd4  Qxd3  29.Rxd3  Nf8  ,  heading to g6 to hassle White's kingside. }
24... Kg8 25. Rd2
{ 25.Rd3  ,  the rook defends on c3 and could also go to f3 at some point.  25...Nf8  26.Rf1  ,  going for the f5-square.  26...Rb7  ,  aiming to create problems for White with moves such as ...b4 and ...Bc4.  27.Nd5  is a good idea, to be able to play ...a4 when we want to break.   27.Na2  ,  aiming to hinder the ...b4 push.  27...Bc4  ,  the bishop is annoying for White here!  28.Rc3   28.Rd2  Ne6  ,  attacking with all of our pieces!  29.Qe3  Nc5  ,  we'll remove the queen from a5 next to push the a-pawn. Even ...Na4 ideas could be possible as well.  After  28...Ne6  29.Qe3  Nc5  ,  won't our attack terrify White?  30.bxc4  ,  engines recommend taking. We still have good resources.  30...Na4+  31.Kc1  Nxc3  32.Qxc3  and White has to take with the queen to protect a3.  32...Qa4  33.Qb3  Qxc4  34.Qxc4  Rxc4  with a rook and a pawn for two knights, the endgame is balanced. We'll soon play ...a5 and ...b4.  27...Bxd5  28.exd5  b4  29.a4  Rbc7  30.Rd2  e6  followed by ...Rc5. If White takes on e6, the knight joins the attack. }
25... Rb7 { Threatening ...b4. } 26. Nd5
{ A.  26.Nd1  with the same idea as Nd5, which is to meet our ...b4 with a4, but keeping this knight on the board.  26...b4  27.a4  Bd7  ,  rerouting the bishop and bringing it to c6.  28.Ne3  Bc6  , when  our plan is ...Nf8-e6 and we could play ...Qc5 as a defensive resource, we have a solid position.  29.Nd5  ,  what a turn the knight has made!   29.f5  is probably one of the moves White wants to make. They sacrifice a pawn but, in exchange, they open the g-file.  29...Nxg5  30.fxg6  fxg6  31.Rg1  Be8  .  In order to move the knight on g5, it's necessary to defend the g6-pawn.  32.Nc4  Qc5  33.Qd3  Kh7  ,  White has to keep pushing to avoid being a pawn down.  34.e5  ,  disconnecting the queen to the g5-knight.  34...Ne6  35.exd6  Qf2  is a brilliant move, freeing the c5-square for the knight.  36.dxe7  Rxe7  and we have plenty of ideas. We can bring a rook to d8, a knight to c5, and the queen to f6.  29...Qc5  ,  by trading queens we release the pressure on our position.  30.Rf1   30.h4  supports the g5-pawn to go for the f5 break.  30...Nf8  with the idea of activating the knight using the e6-square.  31.f5  Bxd5  32.Qxd5  Rbc7  with counterplay on the c-file. Then we'll try to bring the knight to e5.  30...h4  prevents h4 from White in order to weaken the g5-pawn.  31.Qd3   31.Rg1  supports g5 and also adds Rg4 ideas to chase the h4-pawn.  31...e6  32.Ne3  Qxd4+  33.Rxd4  e5  .  The e-pawn breaks the center completely.  34.Rxd6  exf4  35.Nxf4  Bxe4  , when  the pressure on c2 and on g5 give us enough arguments to equalize.  31...e5  ,  blowing up the center. At first sight, your engines will jump with fright, but if you go deeper you will see that it is a good idea!  32.Nf6+  is the critical move.  32...Nxf6  33.gxf6  Rd7  ,  defending d6, and we want to play ...d5!  34.Qf3  with the idea of bringing the queen to h6 to mate us.  34...d5  ,  by the skin of our teeth, but this idea works!  35.Qg4   35.Rg1  with the idea of bringing the queen to h5.  35...dxe4  36.Qh5  Rxd2  ,  going into a forced sequence.  37.Rxg6+  fxg6  38.Qxg6+  Kf8  39.Qg7+  Ke8  40.f7+  Kd8  41.f8=Q+  Qxf8  42.Qxf8+  Be8  ,  counterattacking on c2. The game will end in a draw.  35...Rcc7  36.Qxh4  ,  White continues their plan.  36...dxe4  37.Rxd7  Bxd7  38.Qh6  Qf8  39.Qxf8+  Kxf8  40.fxe5  Rc5  ,  taking on e5 with an equal position.   B. After  26.f5  ,  the exchange of blows begins.  26...b4  27.axb4  Rxb4  28.Qe3  gxf5  29.exf5  Qxf5  and Black wins a pawn, but White has a lot of initiative.  30.Nd4   30.g6  is a good move that weakens the castling.  30...fxg6  31.Nd4  Rxd4  ,  forced; otherwise, the e6-bishop would be hanging.  32.Rxd4  Nf6  ,  when with two pawns for the exchange and good piece activity, we have good chances.  30...Qe5  31.Qxe5  dxe5  32.Nxe6  fxe6  .  What a pawn structure!  33.Re1  ,  White wants to grab some pawns.  33...Rh4  ,  activating the rook.  34.Rh2  is the best defense because the rook on d3 would be more exposed to our knight jumps.  34...Nf8  35.Rxe5  Rd8  with enough activity to compensate for our poor structure. }
26... Bxd5 27. exd5 Nf8 { Time to improve the knight by bringing it to c5. }
28. Rf1 { With the double idea of playing f5 and defend along the 3rd rank. }
28... Nd7 29. Rf3 Qb6 30. Qe4
{ 30.Qxb6  − the exchange of queens has certain venom because White will have pressure on the e-file and can go for the f5 break. Following  30...Rxb6  31.Re3  Kf8  32.Nd4  Rb7  is a good defensive move.  33.f5  gxf5  34.Nxf5  Ne5  ,  doubling on the c-file next; we'll put a rook on c5 and we'll play ...a5 followed by ...b4 with a nice position for Black. }
30... b4 31. a4 Nc5 32. Qd4 Nd7 33. Qxb6
{ 33.Qe4  would be met by  33...Nc5  , so there are no more options available for White. }
33... Nxb6 34. a5
{ Expelling the knight from b6 to be able to play Nd4 without dropping the pawn on d5.   34.f5  is a natural move, gaining some space. If we trade on f5, the h5-pawn will be weak but in return, we win the e5-square for the knight and it won't take long for us to take advantage of it!  34...gxf5  35.Rxf5  Nd7  36.Nf4  ,  White attacks our h5-pawn.  After  36...Ne5  37.Nxh5  ,  both sides have carried out their respective plans, but now we're a pawn down! We'll also make it clear soon that we have adequate compensation.  37...Rc3  38.Rh2  Rbc7  ,  intending to play ...Nf3-d4, getting the material back. }
34... Nd7 35. Nd4 a6
{ If White doesn't prevent it, we will play ...Rc5 and go for the a-pawn. } 36.
c3
{ 36.c4  would be the same thing after taking en passant. Besides,  36.Nc6  would be met with  36...Nb8  and White has nothing better than going back to d4. }
36... bxc3+ 37. Rxc3 Nc5
{ We have a solid position, but White has a two-against-one on the queenside, which could put us in trouble. That's why I keep analyzing this endgame: I don't want you to suffer at all! }
38. Ka2
{ The correct move.  38.Ka3  is worse, as after  38...Rcb8  39.Rdc2  ,  we could play  39...Rb4  because ...Nc6 is not possible since we take on b3 with check. }
38... Rcb8 39. Rdc2 e6
{ The only move that achieves equality. We threaten to take on d5 and after the white capture on e6, the f-file will be opened so that we have counterplay there. }
40. dxe6
{ 40.Nc6  is not a problem for us if we meet it accurately, but there is an ending that may scare us.  40...Rc8  41.b4  exd5  42.bxc5  Rxc6  43.cxd6  Rxd6  .  Everything is forced. Now White conquers our back rank and will try to create mate threats thanks to the presence of their pawn on g5:  44.Rc8+  Kg7  45.Ra8  .  However, it is only necessary to see that with the advance of the f-pawn, we got rid of the mate and forced White to secure a draw.  45...f6  46.Rcc8  d4  and White should go for a draw with the checks along the 8th rank. }
40... fxe6 41. Re3 { Hitting e6. } 41... Rf7
{ Looking for counterplay against the f-pawn. The endgame is equal. } *

