14... Be6 15. Kb1 { 15.f4  Nc6  16.Kb1  will lead to the same position. } 15...
h4
{ For quite a while I was trying to make the  15...a6  16.f4  Rxc3  line work, but White has precise maneuvers at their disposal to get an advantage. }
16. Rhe1 { White confidently strikes in the center. } 16... Nh5
{ Aiming to take advantage of the weakened dark squares. Again we have a double-edged position that will be decided by whoever can calculate the best as for either side to make progress, they will need to take risks and change the position. Let's look at an example:   17.f4  Nc6  18.e5   18.Nd5  ,  White hopes to go into an endgame with the idea to be able to activate the a3-knight after the queen trade.  18...Qxd2  19.Rxd2  Kf8  ,  preempting White's threats. This move is better than ...O-O because we need to keep defending the e7-square.  20.Nb5  a6  21.Nbc7  Bxd5  22.Nxd5  Bh6  followed by ...Kg7 and ...e6 or ...Rhe8, with an equal position.  18...O-O  19.exd6   19.Bxe6  ,  it's difficult to resist for long to weaken our castling.  19...fxe6  20.Qd3  Rf5  21.Ne4  ,  intending to go Ng5. There's no other choice for us than to force matters.  21...Nxf4  22.Bxf4  Rxf4  ,  taking the pawn is now possible because the knight harasses the white queen, which stopped attacking g6.  23.exd6  exd6  and although our pawn structure is ugly, we have good counterplay thanks to the bishop and we can keep the game even. Let's see the important lines.  24.Qe3   24.Qxd6  Qf5  ,  defending on e6 and, at the same time, attacking e4.  25.g4  hxg3  26.Nxg3  Qf7  27.Qxe6  ,  White has won a pawn, but the endgame should be a draw thanks to our active rooks.  27...Rf8  28.Qxf7+  R8xf7  29.c3  ,  intending to bring the knight to c2.  29...Rf3  30.Rg1  Ne5  ,  when our pieces are well coordinated and we definitely have enough compensation for the pawn.  24...Rcf8  − we had the possibility of ...Qg5 but I like to keep playing active, although this gives White a lot of life as well!  25.Nc4  Qa4  26.Ncxd6  ,  what two strong knights White has!  26...Nb4  27.Qb3  Qxb3  28.axb3  b6  with a somewhat cramped ending, but still gives us a chance to equalize. We'll see the most dangerous line.  29.Nc4  R8f5  30.Rd8+  Rf8  31.Rxf8+  Rxf8  32.Ncd2  Rc8  33.c3  Nd3  and Black is fine.  19...exd6  20.f5  Qxf5  21.Bxe6  fxe6  22.Nc4  ,  how much life this knight has!  22...Ne5  23.Nxd6  Nc4  24.Nxf5  Nxd2+  25.Bxd2  exf5  26.Nd5  ,  White has very good pieces, better than ours, so we have to play finely in order not to be worse.  26...Rce8  with the idea of trading a pair of rooks.  27.Bg5  and the h4-pawn will fall.  27...Ng3  28.Bxh4  Rxe1  29.Rxe1  Ne4  .  Although objectively it is a draw, it will be difficult for us to play because we have to be very active, as we're a pawn down. }
