{ I found this idea while preparing for my 2018 Banter Blitz match against IM Paolo Ladrón de Guevara. At that time I was just looking for a line to surprise in blitz, but the deeper I went, the more excited I became about the variation!   Three years later, it is a pleasure for me to share with Chessable users all my analysis of the line. I'm not exaggerating if I tell you that behind the material you will see below the time spent can be counted in thousands of hours.   From here the material is practically virgin, with only 15 games played at the time of writing. So my task is to create practically the whole line in this position.   I gladly accept the challenge and welcome you to The Dragon Sicilian: Wing Attack. The analyses are made almost entirely with the help of the latest versions of Stockfish 12 on a computer with 48 core CPU and some even with more powerful computers!   I am, of course, aware of the evaluation given by the engine, sometimes pointing to a very wide advantage for White, but I ask the reader not to be carried away by these evaluations and to study the ideas I present here.   I am completely convinced that the variation is not only playable in practice, but it also gives much more winning chances than the usual variations. Without further ado, let's jump right in! }
8. Bc4
{ Dodging Black's ideas but, at the same time, accepting the challenge of playing the most aggressive lines against the Dragon. In my original analysis, I have dozens of different possibilities to play against this line but, in the end, I've chosen to play as in the classical line, but with ...h5 and delaying castling.   The idea has the advantage that it makes White's attack on the kingside slower but, on the other hand, the attacks in the center will be more dangerous and we're giving them an immediate break point. }
8... Bd7 9. Qd2 Bg7 10. O-O-O Ne5
{ I was very close to recommending lines with  10...Na5  which work very, very well against  11.Bb3  , which is almost the most played move here. However, it's not as effective against  11.Bd3  or  11.Be2  so I rather recommend the old -but reliable- move. }
11. Bb3 Rc8
{ We have reached the main line of the variation. White has different options, mainly depending on whether they prefer to play in the center or break with g4. }
12. h4
{ It is a somewhat strange attempt to reach known lines if we play  12...O-O  . }
12... a6
{ By delaying castling and going for ...b5, we'll obtain a good position basically because the g4 or Bh6 ideas don't exist and the move h4 contributes very little to White's position. }
13. Kb1 b5 14. Rhe1
{ Once the rook is removed from the h-file, it is a good time to castle. }
14... O-O 15. Bg5 Re8 { A classical move, overprotecting e7. } 16. f4
{ The logical continuation after Rhe1 and Bg5. } 16... Nc4 17. Bxc4 Rxc4 18. e5
Bg4
{ The precise move. We should know this motif: the g5-bishop will be trapped by White's own pawns. }
19. exf6 exf6 20. Rxe8+ Qxe8 21. Re1 Qa8 { The best square for the queen. } 22.
b3 Rxc3
{ Sacrificing the exchange to avoid this knight from creating problems. } 23.
Qxc3 fxg5
{ With that magnificent bishop pair of ours and all of White's kingside pawns under attack, we have a big advantage. }
