Kb1
{ 18.Nxe6  fxe6  19.Nb5  Rc5  20.Nd4   20.c4  a6  21.Nd4  Kf7  ,  let's make this move naturally. Our idea is to play ...Rfc8 and ...b5, but White can still try to keep the initiative.  22.f4  is the critical move, aiming to break the center open.  22...b5  23.Nxe6  is a very interesting knight sacrifice that is very problematic for us and we must know how to face it.   23.e5  − they're coming for us!  23...bxc4  24.Nxe6  and White has come again! The knight cannot be taken because of exd6+.  24...Rd5  25.Qb2   25.Qe2  ,  the queen tries to penetrate through the light squares.  25...cxb3  26.Nxf8  prevents our rook to penetrate via c8.  26...Rc5+  27.Kb1  Nd5  and the entrance on c3 forces White to sacrifice on d5.  28.Rxd5  Rxd5  29.Qc4  bxa2+  30.Ka1  Qb5  .  All this sequence has been forced.  31.Qxb5  Rxb5  32.Kxa2  Bxf8  ,  we're a pawn up. However, with precise play White should be able to hold and get a draw.  25...Rc8  26.exf6  cxb3+  27.Kb1  bxa2+  28.Ka1  and now comes a festival of exchanges.  28...Rxd1+  29.Rxd1  Qxb2+  30.Kxb2  exf6  31.Nxg7  fxg5  32.Nxh5  gxh5  33.fxg5  Ke6  and, again, the endgame is easier to play with Black, but if White plays the correct moves, the game will end in a draw.  23...Kxe6  24.e5  dxe5  .  There are several options, but this move is the most straightforward.  25.Rxe5+  Rxe5  26.fxe5  Qxe5  27.Bxf6  and how do we prevent Re1?  27...Bh6  28.Bxe5  Bxd2+  29.Rxd2  Kxe5  ,  reaching an equal endgame.  20...Rfc8  ,  the counterplay is here! We threaten ...e5.  21.c4  b5  ,  no time to turn back!  22.Nxe6  bxc4  23.Nxc5  cxb3  24.Be3  Kh7  is a precise move that prevents White to take our a2-pawn -when it gets there- with check.  25.Qb2  ,  White has to play a series of only moves for not to be worse.  25...bxa2  26.Qxa2  Qb4  with the idea of ...Nd7.  27.Qb1  Qa5  28.Rd2  is again the only move.  28...Nd7  ,  getting the knight back with huge compensation for the exchange. Let's continue the analysis a bit more.  29.Kd1  Nxc5  ,  taking the knight back. Our position is better thanks to our passed a-pawn, our bishop being on its best diagonal, and also thanks to the fact that our king is safer than White's. }
18... Nh7
{ A curious move that is possible because the rook defends e7. The idea is to clear the long diagonal, so that white cannot play Nxe6. }
19. Be3 a6 { Let's play for ...b5. } 20. h3 { And White plays for g4! } 20...
b5 21. g4 Rfc8 { Attacking on c3, although White can sacrifice this knight! }
22. Nce2
{ Retreating the knight, which may also play a leading role on the kingside soon.   22.gxh5  is an interesting move that greatly complicates the game because both sides are coming very close to the enemy king.  22...Rxc3  23.hxg6  fxg6  24.Nxe6  Rxc2  25.Qd5  ,  in cold blood.  25...Rb2+  26.Ka1  Nf6  ,  moving the queen away from this dangerous diagonal.  27.Qd3  Rcc2  and the other rook joins the party.  28.Bd4  ,  the bishop controls the b2-square and is eyeing g7 as well.  28...Rxa2+  29.Kb1  Ne8  .  Even if it doesn't last long, we give life to the bishop on g7 and, in the last case, we prepare to bring the knight into the game via g7-e6.  30.Nxg7   30.e5  ,  attacking the g6-pawn is a brave move indeed!  30...dxe5  31.Rxe5  is White's idea. We cannot take the e5-rook because of the check on g6.  31...Rcb2+  is the most forcing move.  32.Bxb2  Rxb2+  33.Kxb2  Qxe5+  34.Nd4  Nc7  .  The knight is on its way to e6 to take advantage of the pinned d4-knight.  35.Qxg6  Ne6  36.Qe8+  Kh7  37.Qxe7  Nxd4  38.Qxe5  Bxe5  and the endgame is drawish.  30...Nxg7  31.Rg1  Rg2  ,  preventing the white rook to enter on g6. The position is very complex, but we don't have so many problems with the king. Besides, we can even consider playing ...e5 and then bringing the knight to f4. }
22... h4 { We don't want the kingside to be opened. } 23. Bh6
{ White wants to remove our bishop from the board.  23.Nf4  would be met with  23...Nf8  . }
23... Bc4 { The key idea to continue fighting for the initiative. } 24. Bxg7
Bxe2 25. Qxe2 Kxg7 26. e5 { Practically, White's only attacking resource. }
26... dxe5 27. Qxe5+ Kg8
{ Are we safe? Not quite yet, because we have to face the arrival of Facun.†  †Facun is the name that the chess24 Spanish staff gives to the f-pawn. }
28. f4 Qb6 { Improving the queen's position. } 29. f5 g5
{ The queen can get to f6 to free the knight, while the rooks can enter on c3. }
