7. h3 Bg7
{ Against this slow move we continue by developing the bishop to its natural square. }
8. Bc4 O-O 9. Bb3 { Avoiding all ...Nxe4 ideas. } 9... Na5
{ Keeping the bishop on b3 in range and mainly moving the knight out of the way in order to play ...b6 followed by ...Bb7 and put pressure on e4. }
10. O-O b6 11. Re1
{ 11.Bg5  Bb7  12.Re1  is the other way to reach the main line. } 11... Bb7 12.
Bg5 h6
{ As so many times, we are going to challenge this bishop as soon as we can in order for it to have to choose a diagonal. }
13. Bh4 Qc8 { A precise move aimed to prevent Nd5. } 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5
{ 15.exd5  would be met with  15...Nxb3  and ...Qc5 comes next to put immediate pressure against the d5-pawn. }
15... e6 16. Bxb7 Qxb7
{ There is no doubt that our position is very comfortable. Let's look at some variations. }
17. Bg3 { Aiming to create problems for the d6-pawn. } 17... Rfd8
{ Taking advantage of the fact that the bishop no longer controls this square. }
18. Qd3 { Preventing ...b5 to be able to play c3 without any problems. } 18...
Rac8 19. c3 Nc4
{ Threatening b2 and standing out the fact that the queen is not so well placed on d3. }
20. Qe2 b5
{ Again, hoping to play ...b4. Our position is already better, as White's pieces are not coordinated for any active plan. }
