1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be3
{ The main move. } 6... Nc6
{ A more uncommon move, delaying the development of the Dragon bishop since after most of White's next moves, we have something different in mind for this piece. }
7. h3 Bg7
{ Against this slow move we continue by developing the bishop to its natural square. }
8. Bc4 O-O 9. Bb3 { Avoiding all ...Nxe4 ideas. } 9... Na5
{ Keeping the bishop on b3 in range and mainly moving the knight out of the way in order to play ...b6 followed by ...Bb7 and put pressure on e4. }
10. O-O b6 11. Re1
{ 11.Bg5  Bb7  12.Re1  is the other way to reach the main line. } 11... Bb7 12.
Bg5 h6
{ As so many times, we are going to challenge this bishop as soon as we can in order for it to have to choose a diagonal. }
13. Bxf6
{ I think there is no need to explain that, with these kinds of moves, White will not be able to fight for the advantage. Interestingly, I have more than 200 games between engines where they chose this option. }
13... Bxf6 14. Bd5 { Removing immediately our bishop pair from the board. }
14... Rc8
{ Developing the rook and forcing White to take on b7, as we're threatening ...Ba6, keeping the bishop pair. }
15. Bxb7 Nxb7 16. Nd5 { The only move that justifies White's previous play. }
16... Bg7 17. c3 e6 18. Nb4
{ A somewhat better move than Ne3 with the idea that ...Nc5 by Black doesn't threaten the e4-pawn. }
18... Nc5
{ After ...Qd7, ...Rfd8, and ...Qb7, we'll have a very comfortable position and, possibly, a comfortable advantage as well. }
