[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be3
{ The main move. } 6... Nc6
{ A more uncommon move, delaying the development of the Dragon bishop since after most of White's next moves, we have something different in mind for this piece. }
7. h3 Bg7
{ Against this slow move we continue by developing the bishop to its natural square. }
8. Bc4 O-O 9. O-O { This move allows us to equalize very comfortably. } 9...
Nxe4 10. Bxf7+
{ This is the move that White relied on until the great Alexei Shirov showed the correct reply thanks to a very good win against Michael Adams in 1991. }
10... Kxf7
{ The point is that we need the black queen to be defended by the rook in order to play e5 in the main variation without having to take tactical blows. }
11. Nxe4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e5
{ The point of taking on f7 with the king is that now White cannot play Bc5. }
13. Be3 d5 14. Bg5
{ 14.Ng3  d4  will lead tothe same position as if the bishop had retreated to c3. }
14... Qd7 15. Nc3 { White wants to fight for the initiative. } 15... h6 16. Bh4
d4 17. Ne4 Kg8
{ Obtaining a type of position that we have already seen in the previous lines. White doesn't have a good way to break our center and the bishop pair gives us some advantage. Let's see a possible continuation. }
18. Re1 Qd5 { With the idea of coordinating the queen and the bishop on f5. }
19. f3 { Preempting the threat. } 19... Bf5 20. c3
{ The only way of fighting for the center. } 20... Rac8
{ Getting ready in case the c-file opens up. Our position is very comfortable. }
*

