{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be3
{ The main move. } 6... Nc6
{ A more uncommon move, delaying the development of the Dragon bishop since after most of White's next moves, we have something different in mind for this piece. }
7. h3 Bg7
{ Against this slow move we continue by developing the bishop to its natural square. }
8. Qd2
{ White plays in a similar fashion as in the Yugoslav Attack, but playing h3 instead of f3. The disadvantage is that White cannot launch the typical attack with h4-h5 and, besides, it doesn't overprotect the e4-pawn. On the other hand, the advantage of this approach is the possibility of playing f4 to put pressure on the center. }
8... O-O 9. O-O-O
{ We meet White's approach with the classical and familiar idea... } 9... d5
{ If we can break with ...d5, let's do it! } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12.
Nxd5 { The idea that White plays practically all the time. } 12... cxd5 13.
Qxd5 Qc7
{ A typical move, removing the queen and allowing White to take on a8. } 14.
Qc5 { White looks for an exchange of queens to cash in on the extra pawn. }
14... Qb7 { Threatening the b2-pawn. } 15. b3
{ The correct way of avoiding our threats. Against any other move, the combination of ...Rb7 and ...Bf5 together with bringing a rook to the c-file will be too dangerous for the white king. }
15... Bf5 16. Qa5 { Preempting our idea of bringing a rook to the c-file. }
16... Qc6 { The correct idea! The queen heads to f6. } 17. Bd3 Qf6 18. Bxf5
Qb2+ 19. Kd2 gxf5
{ Having taken the white king out for a walk, it's hard to think we're in trouble but, as always, let's go a little deeper. }
20. Qxf5
{ White manages to grab a second pawn but, in return, the queen leaves the queenside. }
20... Rac8
{ We keep attacking c2 and we threaten to give a check on d8. The attack rages on from here. Let's see how it could continue:   21.Rc1  e6  22.Qe4  is the only move that prevents us from taking on c2 after ...Rfd8.  22...f5  ,  you can take the third pawn if you want!  23.Qxe6+  Kh8  and now we threaten to play ...f4 apart from the check on d8.  24.g3  is the only move.  24...Rfe8  ,  giving up another pawn!  25.Qxf5  and we are almost out of pawns to sacrifice.  25...Qc3+  26.Ke2  Bh6  .  We have a few pawns, but all of our pieces are better than those of our opponent.    27.Qd3  Qc6  ,  threatening to take on e3 and enter on g2.  28.Rhg1  ,  preventing the queen from entering on g2.  28...Rcd8  29.Qc4  Qb6  ,  more fire against the pin.  30.Qc3+  Bg7  31.Qc4  and now we can repeat the position straight away or keep the game alive with the following continuation:  31...Rd4  32.Qf7  Rde4  .  We have the initiative and a better position. }
