Bd4 { Following the main line ideas. } 12... Bxd4 13. Qxd4 Qb6
{ The most solid continuation. } 14. Na4
{ The critical move, avoiding the trades on c3 and heading to c5. } 14... Qc7
{ The best square for the queen. } 15. Bc4
{ Putting pressure on d5 and, at the same time, developing the bishop on its best diagonal. }
15... Rd8 16. Rhe1 { Centralizing the rook but allowing a tactical blow. }
16... Bxh3
{ Sacrificing the bishop to defend the rook on d8 and prepare a discovered attack on the queen. }
17. gxh3 Nb6 18. Qh4 { White wants to take on e7. } 18... Nxa4 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8
20. Qxe7 Qf4+
{ We can bring the rook to the b-file next to continue putting pressure there. I think White's king feels a bit more heat than Black's. }
