[Black "6.Be2 Mainline: 9.Qd2 #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional move. Now White will normally play in the center taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.  The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O { In this case,  7...Nc6  will transpose to this line. } 8.
Be3 Nc6
{ After this move we are ready to break with ...d5. White has many options and we should know and understand their nuances. }
9. Qd2 d5
{ 9...Ng4  or  9...Bd7  are more popular, but I don't see any reason why we have to forget this central pawn break. }
10. Rfd1 { The most solid option. } 10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Nxe4 12. Qxd5 Nd6
{ Avoiding the queen trade, as White's queen is exposed to the attack of our pieces. }
13. Qb3
{ White tries to preempt the threat in order to place the knight in the center. }
13... Be6 14. Nd5 Nf5
{ Interestingly, one of the Dragon experts -the English GM Gawain Jones- has played this position three times already. Are his opponents not able to find a line that could annoy him more than this one? }
15. Bf3 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 Bxd5 { The simplest. } 17. Rxd5 Qc7 18. c3 b6
{ Black will follow with ...Rad8. It is no coincidence that the seven games I have in my database with this position ended in a draw. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) The Principled 6.Be2 / 7.O-O / 8.Be3 Mainline"]
[Black "6.Be2 Mainline: 9.Nb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional move. Now White will normally play in the center taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.  The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O { In this case,  7...Nc6  will transpose to this line. } 8.
Be3 Nc6
{ After this move we are ready to break with ...d5. White has many options and we should know and understand their nuances. }
9. Nb3 { The classical continuation, preventing ...d5. } 9... Be6
{ Of course,  9...a6  is also a playable option, but in this case we'll still try to play ...d5 with the idea of occupying c4. }
10. f4 Rc8
{ More usual is  10...Qc8  but I prefer this more typical Sicilian move as I see no reason why this rook should not get to its favorite square. }
11. Kh1 { It's never a bad time to remove the king from the diagonal. } 11...
a6
{ Preparing  ...b5  . I like this move more than  11...Na5  as after  12.Nxa5  Qxa5  13.Bd3!  White somehow controls the position. }
12. Bf3 Bc4
{ Is there any reason why we shouldn't take advantage of the square that the bishop doesn't control anymore? }
13. Rf2 e5
{ The usual idea is to hassle the bishop on f3 and, at the same time, we try to get the e5-square for our knight. If White plays f5, we change plans and play ...d5. }
14. Rd2
{ The only problem of Black's ...e5 is that the d6-pawn is now a backward pawn. }
14... exf4 15. Rxd6 Qc7 16. Bxf4 Ne8
{ Taking advantage of the fact that the rook cannot move because the bishop on f4 is hanging. }
17. Nd5 { White continues fighting for the initiative. } 17... Bxd5
{ Starting a series of trades. } 18. Qxd5 Nxd6 19. Bxd6 Qd8 20. Bxf8 Qxf8
{ In exchange for the pawn we have very good control of the dark squares and better coordination than White. }
21. c3 Be5
{ We will follow with moves such as ...Rd8 and ...Qh6 and our minor pieces do a great job controlling the center of the board. }
