[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) The Principled 6.Be2 / 7.O-O / 8.Be3 Mainline"]
[Black "6.Be2 Mainline: 9.Nb3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional move. Now White will normally play in the center taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.  The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O { In this case,  7...Nc6  will transpose to this line. } 8.
Be3 Nc6
{ After this move we are ready to break with ...d5. White has many options and we should know and understand their nuances. }
9. Nb3 { The classical continuation, preventing ...d5. } 9... Be6
{ Of course,  9...a6  is also a playable option, but in this case we'll still try to play ...d5 with the idea of occupying c4. }
10. f4 Rc8
{ More usual is  10...Qc8  but I prefer this more typical Sicilian move as I see no reason why this rook should not get to its favorite square. }
11. Bf3
{ The bishop on f3 wants to have some activity with e5, so we immediately react with the following idea; if you have already studied other lines of the course, you will be familiar with it. }
11... Bc4 { Hitting the rook to play ...e5 next. } 12. Rf2 e5
{ With this move, we punish the bishop on f3 and we want to get the e5-square for the knight. It's not all good news since d6 is obviously weak now. }
13. Rd2 { Attacking the weakness. } 13... exf4 14. Bxf4 Ne8
{ We calmly defend the pawn on d6. At the same time, we open the long diagonal and enable move ...Ne5 move. }
15. Bxd6
{ Although this is not the best move, it's the only one that allows us to follow the natural plan: we'll play ...Ne5 and push on the queenside. }
15... Nxd6 16. Rxd6 Qb6+
{ There is no need to talk about compensation because with a precise sequence, we will get the pawn back with an advantage. }
17. Kh1 Be5 { Bringing the rook to a worse square. } 18. Rd2
{ 18.Rd7  is met by  18...Bxc3  and winning a tempo with ...Ne5 next. } 18...
Bxc3 19. bxc3 Qe3
{ White cannot prevent us to take on c3. With such a sad structure, the first player will have a difficult game ahead. }
