{ Overprotecting e4 to prevent the pawn from falling after the typical sacrifice on c3. }
13... gxf5 14. exf5
{ 14.gxf5  is simply met by  14...Kh8  intending to play ...Rg8 and it's Black who attacks on the open file! White will not be able to copy Black's plan so easily because the bishop will target the white king from c6. }
14... e6 { Opening the position! } 15. Nde4 exf5
{ White's castling will suffer more than Black's. } 16. gxf5 Kh8
{ Followed by ...Rg8 and ...Bc6 with a practically decisive attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) The Principled 6.Be2 / 7.O-O / 8.Be3 Mainline"]
[Black "6.Be2 Mainline: 9.Nb3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional move. Now White will normally play in the center taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.  The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O { In this case,  7...Nc6  will transpose to this line. } 8.
Be3 Nc6
{ After this move we are ready to break with ...d5. White has many options and we should know and understand their nuances. }
9. Nb3 { The classical continuation, preventing ...d5. } 9... Be6
{ Of course,  9...a6  is also a playable option, but in this case we'll still try to play ...d5 with the idea of occupying c4. }
10. f4 Rc8
{ More usual is  10...Qc8  but I prefer this more typical Sicilian move as I see no reason why this rook should not get to its favorite square. }
11. f5
{ The most aggressive continuation is, in this case, somewhat dubious, as it gives up the e5-square for our knight. }
11... Bd7 12. g4 { In for a penny, in for a pound! } 12... Ne5
{ The promised square. } 13. Bd4
{ Trying to prevent the exchange sacrifice from doubling pawns on the c-file, but that is only one of White's many problems. }
13... Rxc3
{ Certainly  13...Bc6  is also good and Black can obtain enough advantage without sacrificing the exchange. }
14. Bxc3 Nxe4 15. Bd4
{ White has managed to keep the structure but in return has lost too many tempi and we can take advantage of this to continue lighting up the position. }
15... e6
{ A typical move that threatens to take on f5 and facilitate our queen to be transferred to the kingside. The position is extremely difficult for White. }
*

