[Black "6.Be2 Mainline: 9.Nb3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional move. Now White will normally play in the center taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.  The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O { In this case,  7...Nc6  will transpose to this line. } 8.
Be3 Nc6
{ After this move we are ready to break with ...d5. White has many options and we should know and understand their nuances. }
9. Nb3 { The classical continuation, preventing ...d5. } 9... Be6
{ Of course,  9...a6  is also a playable option, but in this case we'll still try to play ...d5 with the idea of occupying c4. }
10. f4 Rc8
{ More usual is  10...Qc8  but I prefer this more typical Sicilian move as I see no reason why this rook should not get to its favorite square. }
11. f5
{ The most aggressive continuation is, in this case, somewhat dubious, as it gives up the e5-square for our knight. }
11... Bd7 12. Qe1
{ An attempt to bring the queen into the attack, but White will miss the presence of the knights on the kingside. }
12... Ne5 13. Qh4 b5
{ Reacting without wasting time on the queenside. It's not possible to play  14.Bxb5  due to  14...Rxc3  whereas  14.Nxb5  would allow the rook to enter on c2. }
14. a3 a5 { Insisting! } 15. Nd4
{ Centralizing the knight and, at the same time, defending c2. } 15... b4 16.
axb4 axb4 17. Nd5 { 17.Nd1  is very annoying and allows  17...d5  . } 17...
gxf5
{ As simple as that. White cannot take with the knight on f5 because c2 would be hanging in that case. }
18. Bh6 { Accumulating pieces on the kingside. } 18... Ng6
{ The key defensive move.  19.Qh3  would be met by  19...f4  so White should trade on f6. }
19. Nxf6+ Bxf6 20. Qf2 fxe4 { Sacrificing the exchange. } 21. Bxf8 Qxf8
{ With two pawns, the bishop pair, and a good center, together with a nice activity of our pieces, we can't ask for much more from life! The position is close to winning for Black. }
