[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) The Principled 6.Be2 / 7.O-O / 8.Be3 Mainline"]
[Black "6.Be2 Mainline: 9.Nb3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional move. Now White will normally play in the center taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.  The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O { In this case,  7...Nc6  will transpose to this line. } 8.
Be3 Nc6
{ After this move we are ready to break with ...d5. White has many options and we should know and understand their nuances. }
9. Nb3 { The classical continuation, preventing ...d5. } 9... Be6
{ Of course,  9...a6  is also a playable option, but in this case we'll still try to play ...d5 with the idea of occupying c4. }
10. f4 Rc8
{ More usual is  10...Qc8  but I prefer this more typical Sicilian move as I see no reason why this rook should not get to its favorite square. }
11. g4
{ White starts the attack without giving up the e5-square for the black knight. A good idea, indeed! }
11... Na5
{ We would rather jump to e5 but here our position is not bad either! } 12. f5
{ White pushes the f-pawn, when Black's knight cannot get to e5 in one move. }
12... Bc4 13. Bd3
{ A usual move before the bishop arrives at c4. White wants us to exchange on d3 to fix their structure since the pawn on d3 controls c4 and protects e4. }
13... Nd7
{ A familiar move for all of us. The coordination of our pieces is beautiful! }
14. Kh1 { A very useful move to avoid the checks along the diagonal. } 14... b5
{ There are other normal moves, but I like to keep developing the initiative with this pawn sacrifice. }
15. Nxb5
{ White doesn't want to allow us to arrive quickly to the queenside without paying a price for it. }
15... Bxb5 16. Bxb5 Nc4 17. Bc1
{ The only move that keeps White in the game. Trading on c4 gives nothing good as we'll recapture and attack on e4.  If  17.Bd4  we'll take on b2.  The idea of  17.Bc1  is to meet the move  17...Nxb2  with  18.Qe2  ,  trapping the knight. No problem, let's play being a pawn down! }
17... Nde5 18. g5
{ A natural attacking move, trying to neutralize the monster bishop on g7 with f6.  18.c3  is more solid, and can be met with  18...Qb6  . }
18... d5
{ A fantastic central reaction! Our advantage in development gives us the opportunity to open the position immediately. }
19. exd5 gxf5 { The point! } 20. Rxf5 e6
{ An elegant way of getting the pawn back. } 21. Rf1 Qb6
{ We don't even worry about getting the pawn back since, by forcing the exchange of the bishop, the light squares will be very weak and White will not be able to move the d5-pawn. }
22. Bxc4 Rxc4
{ The rook can collaborate in the siege on the white king by switching to g4. Although we are two pawns down, the compensation for them is more than enough, and we are likely to get at least one pawn back fairly soon after ...Rd8 and ...Qb7. }
*

