10. f4 Rc8
{ More usual is  10...Qc8  but I prefer this more typical Sicilian move as I see no reason why this rook should not get to its favorite square. }
11. Qe1 { Intending to play Rd1 next. } 11... b5
{ A novelty! We immediately throw everything at White. We're threatening ...b4 and we also support the move ...Bc4. If White doesn't take on b5, we will certainly have got away with it. }
12. Bxb5 Ng4
{ The point of the pawn sacrifice. White's bishop cannot hide now. } 13. Bxc6
{ We can only think about making these kinds of moves when we understand that the knight jumps are more annoying than usual! }
13... Nxe3 14. Qxe3 Rxc6
{ If white chooses to play quietly, we can continue with ...Bc4 and ...Qb6, with a nice position, so we should analyze the only critical continuation. }
15. Qxa7 Bxc3
{ Concrete play! We get a pawn back and we continue putting pressure on the queenside. }
16. bxc3 Rxc3 17. Rf2 { Defending c2. } 17... Qd7
{ We don't fear going into an endgame because our pieces will put a lot of pressure on White's queenside. }
18. Qxd7 Bxd7 19. a4 { Trying to make the passed pawn count. } 19... Bc8
{ We reroute the bishop in a very elegant way since on a6 it will operate on an important diagonal while slowing down the advance of the passed pawn. The rook on f8 will reach c8 and the compensation will be more than enough to equalize but no more than that. }
