[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) The Principled 6.Be2 / 7.O-O / 8.Be3 Mainline"]
[Black "6.Be2 Mainline: 9.f4 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional move. Now White will normally play in the center taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.  The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O { In this case,  7...Nc6  will transpose to this line. } 8.
Be3 Nc6
{ After this move we are ready to break with ...d5. White has many options and we should know and understand their nuances. }
9. f4 { The most aggressive variation. } 9... Qb6
{ Playing immediately on the recently weakened diagonal. We should point out that  9...Bd7  ,  with the idea of ...Nxd4 and ...Bc6, is not as well known but is a less concrete and perfectly playable option. }
10. e5
{ An aggressive yet dubious move, but we must know very well how to answer that because is not easy to play the right moves on the board if we do not remember them. }
10... dxe5 11. fxe5 Nxe5 { Let's grab the pawn! } 12. Nf5 Qxb2
{ We take everything! } 13. Nxe7+ Kh8 14. Bd4
{ This is White's idea. The next move is the key. } 14... Qb4
{ Removing the queen from shenanigans and, at the same time, hitting the e7-knight. }
15. Bxe5 Qxe7 16. Qd4 { White continues to pressure us. } 16... Nh5 17. Bxg7+
Nxg7 { White's initiative is close to an end. } 18. Bf3
{ Trying to play against our queenside. } 18... Be6 19. Rab1 Rfd8
{ We give the pawn back in return for some initiative. } 20. Rxb7 Qxb7 21.
Qxd8+ Rxd8 22. Bxb7 Nf5
{ The endgame is somewhat better for us, although with correct play -and some suffering- White should manage to equalize. }
*

