[Black "6.Be2 Mainline: 9.h3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional move. Now White will normally play in the center taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.  The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O { In this case,  7...Nc6  will transpose to this line. } 8.
Be3 Nc6
{ After this move we are ready to break with ...d5. White has many options and we should know and understand their nuances. }
9. h3 { Controlling g4. } 9... d5
{ Does White have anything prepared against the break? } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5
{ White's idea is t play Bf3 and trade on c6 next. It is not clear that we can fully equalize there so we are aiming to go to another position. }
11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Qxd5 13. Bxg7 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Kxg7
{ White has the open file under control, the bishop will get to f3 and, being their turn, they still hope to get some advantage. }
15. Bf3
{ Does this move hinder the development of Black's light-squared bishop? }
15... Be6 { Not really! } 16. b3 { White wants to take on b7 now. } 16... Rab8
{ In this case, a passive defense is the best option. } 17. Bd5
{ As White has played b3 already, this move has a bit more venom, but fortunately, not much. }
17... Bxd5 18. Rxd5 Rfc8
{ There are several ways to equality, but this one seems the simplest to me. }
19. c4 Kf8 20. Rfd1 e6 21. Rd7 Ke8 { Black will follow with ...Rd8 next. } *

