{ This move is aimed at gaining some space on the queenside, but but it doesn't add much to White's position against Black's typical pawn break. }
9... d5 10. exd5 Nb4
{ 10...Nxd5  11.Nxd5  Nxd4  is enough to equalize, but I couldn't resist recommending this move since White's a-pawn will no longer be able to control this square. }
11. Bf3 Nfxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5
{ Obviously, Black is completely fine here. We want to play ...e5 so White will try to pin the pawn. }
13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 g5 15. Bg3 Nf4
{ By winning tempo after tempo against the bishop, we have managed to give our knight this nice square. Our position is already preferable. }
