[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) The Principled 6.Be2 / 7.O-O Sidelines"]
[Black "The Principled 6.Be2 Sidelines: 8.Bg5 / 10.a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional move. Now White will normally play in the center taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.  The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O { In this case,  7...Nc6  will transpose to this line. } 8.
Bg5
{ A move that became fashionable in the late 70s after Karpov won in nice style against Miles. }
8... Nc6 9. Nb3
{ Without the bishop on e3, it's better for the knight to retreat to b3, as it avoids being hit on d4 and also helps White control the d5-square. }
9... a6
{ My favorite move in this position, threatening ...b5 and, if White prevents it with a4, we'll try to show that this move will be beneficial for us. }
10. a4 { Preventing ...b5 is the best option for White. } 10... Be6
{ Once we forced the move a4 we will choose b3 as our target. } 11. Kh1
{ Removing the king to play f4 without allowing shenanigans on the diagonal. }
11... Na5
{ Coordinating the knight and bishop immediately on b3. White may notice the absence of the bishop on e3 since the b6-square is no longer controlled. Therefore, it will be through that square that our queen will enter. }
12. f4 Nxb3
{ 12...Rc8  is also a very playable possibility, but I prefer this concrete line. }
13. cxb3 Qb6
{ Let's attack the weakness!  14.Bc4  is not possible because we will take on b2 after trading on c4. Now, if White wants to maintain the material balance, they have to defend really passively with the rook. }
14. Ra3 Qe3
{ We continue harassing White with our queen. From e3 we not only hit e4 but also prevent f5 because the bishop on g5 would be hanging. Now we will meet  15.Bf3  with the quiet move  15...a5  , 'taming' White. }
15. Rf3 { The best option. White tries to grab the initiative. } 15... Qc5
{ With the queen maneuver we made sure that the rook is on f3, taking the square away from the bishop. }
16. f5
{ The point of this move is to meet  16...gxf5  with  17.b4!  and take on f5 next. Although playable, I don't like to weaken our castling that easily. }
16... Bd7 17. b4
{ This good move manages to justify White's rook position on a3. } 17... Qxb4
18. Rb3 Qa5 19. Rxb7 { How quickly life has changed for this rook! } 19... Bc6
{ 19...Rfb8  is more solid but, with careful analysis, we don't have to worry about the complications. }
20. Rxe7 Qd8
{ Trapping White's rook. Now White has two ways to sacrifice it. Let's take a look at how play may continue from here:   21.fxg6  ,  White sacrifices the rook in return for destroying our fianchetto.  21...Qxe7  22.gxh7+  Kh8  23.Qf1  ,  White ensures getting the material back on f6.  23...Bxe4  ,  it was high time for this pawn to fall! Now follows a long sequence of captures until a more or less balanced position is reached.  24.Nxe4  Qxe4  25.Bxf6  Bxf6  26.Rxf6  Qxa4  27.Rxd6  ,  Threatening Qf6+.  After  27...f5  ,  White has two pawns for the exchange and also has an eye on a6. The position is equal but no more.   21.Rxf7  is a nice immolation of the rook on f7. The entry of the white bishop on c4 is imminent.  21...Rxf7  22.Bc4  − engines teach us that compensation is sufficient but, without a doubt, you have to have a very great understanding of the dynamic game to assimilate it.  22...Raa7  ,  we have several moves at our disposal, but connecting the rooks on the 2nd rank can't be a bad idea.  23.fxg6  hxg6  24.Nd5  ,  White keeps bringing their pieces to the party.    24...Bxd5  25.Bxd5  Qe7  ,  controlling the e5 push, that was a very important threat because the queen on d8 was undefended.  26.Bxf7+  Qxf7  27.Qf1  ,  White keeps adding pieces to the pin!  27...Rc7  ,  counterpunching on the back rank.  28.Kg1  − had White decided to advance the h-pawn then we could have taken on e4 and given a check on g3. This move doesn't avoid Black's reaction either.  28...Nxe4  ,  forcing matters.  29.Rxf7  Bd4+  30.Kh1  Rxf7  .  Our attack is a bit scary, but we can only finish the game in a perpetual check. }
