6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O { In this case,  7...Nc6  will transpose to this line. } 8.
Bg5
{ A move that became fashionable in the late 70s after Karpov won in nice style against Miles. }
8... Nc6 9. Nb3
{ Without the bishop on e3, it's better for the knight to retreat to b3, as it avoids being hit on d4 and also helps White control the d5-square. }
9... a6
{ My favorite move in this position, threatening ...b5 and, if White prevents it with a4, we'll try to show that this move will be beneficial for us. }
10. a4 { Preventing ...b5 is the best option for White. } 10... Be6
{ Once we forced the move a4 we will choose b3 as our target. } 11. f4
{ As we will see many times in this course, this move is very dangerous if the king is not on h1. }
11... b5 { The key to be able to execute this move is the check on b6. } 12.
axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Qb6+
{ A finesse. The idea is to be allowed to take on a8 with the rook. } 14. Kh1
Rxa8 { The position is good for us. If White takes on b5, we can take on e4. }
15. Nd5 Bxd5 { Giving up the bishop pair, but keeping the initiative. } 16.
exd5 Na5 17. Nxa5 Rxa5
{ Moves such as ...Ra2, ...b4, and ...Qc5 are coming, dominating White. } *

