[White "10) The Principled 6.Be2 / 7.O-O Sidelines"]
[Black "The Principled 6.Be2 Sidelines: 8.Bg5 / 10.Re1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional move. Now White will normally play in the center taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.  The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O { In this case,  7...Nc6  will transpose to this line. } 8.
Bg5
{ A move that became fashionable in the late 70s after Karpov won in nice style against Miles. }
8... Nc6 9. Nb3
{ Without the bishop on e3, it's better for the knight to retreat to b3, as it avoids being hit on d4 and also helps White control the d5-square. }
9... a6
{ My favorite move in this position, threatening ...b5 and, if White prevents it with a4, we'll try to show that this move will be beneficial for us. }
10. Re1
{ Freeing the f1-square for the bishop and, at the same time, activating the rook to overprotect the e4-pawn. }
10... b5 { Threatening ...b4. } 11. Bf1 { Just in time to defend e4. } 11... h6
{ It's useful to force the white bishop to define its position. The move Nd5 is going to come sooner or later and after the trade on d5, we want to have ...g5 at our disposal so that the bishop is not troublesome on e7. Besides, the bishop on h4 is very poorly placed to collaborate with the rest of the pieces on the queenside. }
12. Bh4 Bd7
{ Practically, a novelty. The development of the bishop to d7, instead of the more natural ...Bb7, is understood as a response to a4. The bishop will be much better placed on d7, attacking a4 and also not blocking the b-file.   If White decides to play without a4, our bishop will look a bit passive on d7, but isn't it enough merit to have prevented White's plan? }
13. a4
{ The move that you are going to face the most in this position, although it's not the best one! }
13... b4 14. Nd5
{ I find it hard to believe  14.Na2  is a serious option, but in this case, I will recommend  14...Qc7  and we'll keep on enjoying the game. }
14... Nxd5 15. exd5 Ne5 16. Qd2
{ A natural move that improves the queen while attacking b4.  16.f4  can be met with  16...Ng4  in coordination with ...Qb6+. }
16... g5 17. Bg3 Ng6
{ This maneuver is aimed at supporting our ideas in the center and, at the same time, we open completely the diagonal for our bishop. Practically, we are going to put pressure on the queenside for free while White has no plan to harass us on the kingside or in the center. }
