13. Nd5 { Immediately seizing the center. } 13... Nxd5 14. exd5 Ne5
{ We will play ...Re8 against almost any move by White, intending to overprotect e7. Later on, we will continue with ...Rc8 and, depending on the circumstances, with ...Bf5, ...Qb6, or ...g5. We just have to remember how to continue if White goes straight to the throat. Let's see how the game could develop:   15.f4  is the most direct move, 'dreaming' about the capture on e7.  15...Nc4  16.Bxc4  bxc4  17.Nd4  and now we have several effective answers, but I recommend the most ambitious one.  17...Qb6  18.Bf2  Qxb2  19.Rb1  Qxa2  20.Rb7  ,  White will manage to capture on e7 and will have some initiative, but with precise play, we can disarticulate it!    20...Bc8  21.Rbxe7  Bf6  22.R7e4  ,  overprotecting the knight  22...c3  ,  fixing the weakness on c2 and, at the same time, attacking d5 with the queen.  23.Nc6  is the only move to stay in the game.  23...Bf5  ,  keeping the initiative.  24.Ne7+  is again the only move.  24...Bxe7  25.Rxe7  Qa4  is a very precise move, preventing Qd4 and a great part of White's counterplay. We hit f4 and c2 and, if that wasn't enough, we can proceed to push the a-pawn. White has a tough fight ahead if they want to draw this game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) The Principled 6.Be2 / 7.O-O Sidelines"]
[Black "The Principled 6.Be2 Sidelines: 8.Bg5 / 10.Kh1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional move. Now White will normally play in the center taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.  The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O { In this case,  7...Nc6  will transpose to this line. } 8.
Bg5
{ A move that became fashionable in the late 70s after Karpov won in nice style against Miles. }
8... Nc6 9. Nb3
{ Without the bishop on e3, it's better for the knight to retreat to b3, as it avoids being hit on d4 and also helps White control the d5-square. }
9... a6
{ My favorite move in this position, threatening ...b5 and, if White prevents it with a4, we'll try to show that this move will be beneficial for us. }
10. Kh1
{ With all the problems we have seen occurring on the diagonal, it is normal for White to want to remove the king before pushing the f-pawn! }
10... b5 { Threatening ...b4. } 11. a3 Bb7 12. f4
{ There is no time left to better prepare this move. } 12... Na5
{ The knight frees the diagonal for the b7-bishop to attack e4. } 13. Nxa5 Qxa5
14. Bf3
{ 14.e5  is a good try, but after  14...dxe5  15.fxe5  and  15...b4!  Black's queen works on the 4th rank to get a nice position. }
14... Qc7 { The queen retreats to control e5 and to defend c7. } 15. Qd2
{ Clearing the way for the a1-rook to come into play. } 15... Rad8
{ Prophylaxis against any e5 attempt by White. } 16. Rae1 Rfe8
{ Freeing the queen from the defense of e7 both to be able to execute the Nd7-b6 maneuver and to be able to annoy White with moves such as ...Qc4. }
17. f5 Nd7 { Here we see the usefulness of having the e7-pawn defended. } *

