1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional approach. With this move, White will normally play in the center, taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.   The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. Be3
{ Here we're going to analyze the lines where White plays with Be2 and Be3 without castling short. This is an aggressive approach whose main difference with f3 is the control of the g4-square. }
7... O-O 8. Qd2
{ One of the most dangerous ideas for Black to face, that has been played by several top Grandmasters, including the one and only Magnus Carlsen! }
8... Nc6 9. O-O-O
{ Now we have two interesting options at our disposal that we will choose according to the kind of position we want to play. }
9... d5
{ The central pawn break leads practically by force to an interesting queen vs 2-rook endgame. }
10. exd5
{ 10.Nxc6  will transpose to the same thing after  10...bxc6  11.exd5  Nxd5  . }
10... Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Qxd5
{ Taking this central pawn is not free for White since it opens up diagonals and files that Black is better prepared to take advantage of. }
13... Qc7 14. Qxa8 Bf5 15. Qxf8+ Kxf8
{ White may be very satisfied with the material exchange -two rooks and pawn for a queen- but Black is better coordinated and White's play is not easy. }
16. Rd2 Qb8
{ Another good alternative is  16...h5  to follow with ...Kg8 and not worry about back-rank mate ideas. }
17. b3 Bc3
{ Winning a tempo while we get the g7-square for our king. To prevent this, White must put their bishop on a square that, although attractive, is not ideal. }
18. Bh6+ Kg8
{ Interestingly, in the two games in which this position has been reached, Black has played  18...Ke8  , that loses because of  19.Rd5  followed by Bb5. }
19. Rdd1
{ The most natural move. In this case, it's not advisable to play  19.Rd5  in view of  19...Be4  . }
19... a5 { Aiming to create new weaknesses around White's king. } 20. a4 e6
{ The idea of this move is to be able to go ...Bf6 followed by ...Qe5. The move ...e6 is necessary for the bishop to control the d8-square from f6. }
21. h4
{ This move is of inhuman finesse. The idea is that after the mentioned plan,  ...Bf6  and  ...Qe5  , White will defend playing Bd3 and trading on f5.  We will meet the trade on f5 by taking with the g-pawn, but with the move h4 on the board White could play Rh3 for Rg3. Had White played  21.Bd3  directly, our follow-up would be  21...Qb4  . }
21... Qc7 { Threatening ...Bg7 and invading on c2. } 22. Bc4 { The only move. }
22... Qe7 { Threatening to enter on a3. } 23. Kb1 Bf6
{ An attempt to set up the battery with ...Qc5-e5 or ...Qb4-c3. White still has a defense against these plans, and the position is objectively equal. }
