{ Now we have two interesting options at our disposal that we will choose according to the kind of position we want to play. }
9... d5
{ The central pawn break leads practically by force to an interesting queen vs 2-rook endgame. }
10. exd5
{ 10.Nxc6  will transpose to the same thing after  10...bxc6  11.exd5  Nxd5  . }
10... Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Qxd5
{ Taking this central pawn is not free for White since it opens up diagonals and files that Black is better prepared to take advantage of. }
13... Qc7 14. Qc4
{ Hoping for the queen trade but, of course, we'll not make the opponent's dreams come true! }
14... Qb7 { Hitting b2 and g2. } 15. Bd4 Bf5
{ First of all, initiative! The bishop is activated while freeing the c8-square for the rooks. }
16. Qb3
{ The best move to calm the waters, coming to an even ending after the following sequence: }
16... Rac8 17. Qxb7 Rxc2+ 18. Kb1 Rc7+ 19. Bd3 Bxd3+ 20. Rxd3 Rxb7
{ We have to be careful in this endgame because White's 2 vs 1 pawn majority can be faster than our central one. After the trade of bishops, it is convenient to launch as soon as possible the f- and e-pawns and activate our king to be ready for the race to come. }
