[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) The Aggressive 6.Be2 without O-O"]
[Black "6.Be2 without O-O: 8.f4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional approach. With this move, White will normally play in the center, taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.   The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. Be3
{ Here we're going to analyze the lines where White plays with Be2 and Be3 without castling short. This is an aggressive approach whose main difference with f3 is the control of the g4-square. }
7... O-O 8. f4 Nc6 9. a3
{ The idea of this mysterious move is to be able to castle short without being annoyed by the move ...Qb6. But, why? The reason is simple: now the queen wouldn't threaten to take on b2 in view of Na4. }
9... Bg4
{ The most simple move to equalize. As we have already explained,  9...Qb6  is not advisable because after  10.Nf5  Qxb2  11.Na4  ,  we have to give up the queen. }
10. h3
{ Forcing the trade, but the main goal is to control g4 for the e3-bishop to be safe on that square. }
10... Bxe2 11. Ndxe2 b5
{ There is no time to waste! 11...b5 is a typical move when the e4-pawn is only defended tby the knight. }
12. Qd3 { Defending the e4-pawn to be able to jump with the knight to d5. }
12... b4 13. Nd5 bxa3 14. Rxa3
{ It's important to understand this type of position well because if we play it carelessly, we can be inferior very easily since our a-pawn can suffer in exchange for nothing. }
14... a5
{ The pawn is no longer in the bishop's range and also supports the knight's jump to b4. }
15. c3 { Preventing ...Nb4 and limiting the action of the g7-bishop. } 15...
Nd7
{ We remove the knight and threaten ...e6, as the d5-knight has no good squares to go to. }
16. Qb5
{ White seeks to support the jump to b6 while hitting the knight on c6: it can't be a bad idea! }
16... Rc8
{ Defending the knight and the next move will be ...e6. After that, the knight will be forced to jump to b6 and after trading everything, we'll play ...Rb8 and we'll try to take on b2! This is how White's next move can be understood. }
17. Ra2 e6 18. Nb6 Nxb6 19. Qxb6 Qd7
{ Once b2 is defended, I think that it's better to keep the queens on the board to continue fighting for the win. }
20. O-O Rc7
{ Followed by ...Rb8 and doubling rooks on the b-file, with a very comfortable position. }
