[Round "?"]
[White "11) The Aggressive 6.Be2 without O-O"]
[Black "6.Be2 without O-O: 8.f4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional approach. With this move, White will normally play in the center, taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.   The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. Be3
{ Here we're going to analyze the lines where White plays with Be2 and Be3 without castling short. This is an aggressive approach whose main difference with f3 is the control of the g4-square. }
7... O-O 8. f4 Nc6 9. a3
{ The idea of this mysterious move is to be able to castle short without being annoyed by the move ...Qb6. But, why? The reason is simple: now the queen wouldn't threaten to take on b2 in view of Na4. }
9... Bg4
{ The most simple move to equalize. As we have already explained,  9...Qb6  is not advisable because after  10.Nf5  Qxb2  11.Na4  ,  we have to give up the queen. }
10. Bxg4
{ The most forced option and that entails a certain danger because White can take advantage of it to develop some initiative on the kingside. }
10... Nxg4 11. Qxg4 Nxd4 12. O-O-O Nc6
{ We have a very solid position and we also threaten to take on c3 by giving our bishop but significantly weakening Black's castling. }
13. e5
{ White is putting pressure in the center while blocking the long diagonal. }
13... Qa5
{ Unpinning and, at the same time, bringing pieces to the queenside. } 14. h4
{ And White is still going after our king! } 14... dxe5
{ Not only unlocking the long diagonal, but we also win a pawn! } 15. f5
{ This is White's idea, who wants to break twice on g6. We must reply accurately because White's threats are very real. }
15... gxf5
{ A seemingly dangerous move. However, with precise play, we'll be able to stop White's attack. }
16. Qxf5 Qa6
{ The idea of this move is to bring the queen to the kingside after ...Nd4. Once we got an extra pawn, it's time to defend, and then we'll use the advantage material later! }
17. Ne4 { Threatening Ng5. } 17... Nd4 18. Bxd4 exd4
{ Our next move is ...Qg6, seeking the queen trade. If White wants to avoid it, they can practically only choose to advance the h-pawn. }
19. h5 h6
{ Stopping the pawn, before it creates too much trouble for us! A very safe move as well is  19...Qe6  and Black has a better endgame. }
20. g4
{ As always, Black should try to open the kingside!  20...--  21.g5  is coming, but we should reply with a fearless move. }
20... Rac8 { The classic counterplay along the c-file. } 21. g5 Qc6 22. Rd2
{ Both sides combine attack and defense. } 22... Kh8
{ Prophylaxis. The g-file is going to open up, so the sooner we get the king out of there, the better! }
23. Rg1 Qe6
{ We have played enough! Let's trade queens and enjoy being a pawn up. } *

