3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional approach. With this move, White will normally play in the center, taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.   The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. Be3
{ Here we're going to analyze the lines where White plays with Be2 and Be3 without castling short. This is an aggressive approach whose main difference with f3 is the control of the g4-square. }
7... O-O 8. f3
{ Playing f3 after Be2 does not make much sense and is a waste of time more than anything else. Black can achieve a very comfortable position by going for a fast central break. }
8... Nc6 9. O-O d5
{ Practically every time we can make this move, we have to do it! After we finish development, we break into the center. }
10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. e5
{ The only way to try to put Black in some trouble even if it's at a cost of a tempo compared to other lines! }
11... Ne8
{ The reason I chose this move over  11...Nd7  , which is also perfectly playable, is that I like the knight's prospects  on d6, from where it threatens to jump to a ton of squares. }
12. f4 { The e5-pawn has to be supported. } 12... f6 13. Bf3
{ A clever tactical resource for which we have to be well prepared. } 13...
fxe5 { Accepting White's challenge! } 14. Nxd5
{ This is the idea behind the move Bf3. Now Black can't take the knight due to the fact that the rook on a8 is hanging. }
14... e4
{ A precise in-between move that will allow us to take the initiative. } 15.
Bxe4 Nd6 16. Nc3 Nxe4 { Don't miss the opportunity to capture this bishop! }
17. Nxe4 Bxb2 { Not even this pawn! } 18. Rb1 Bg7
{ The position is more or less even. However, if White allows us to bring our queen to a5, we could start creating some play! }
*

