[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) The Aggressive 6.Be2 without O-O"]
[Black "6.Be2 without O-O: 8.Nb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional approach. With this move, White will normally play in the center, taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.   The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. Be3
{ Here we're going to analyze the lines where White plays with Be2 and Be3 without castling short. This is an aggressive approach whose main difference with f3 is the control of the g4-square. }
7... O-O 8. Nb3 { A knight retreat which hides really aggressive intentions. }
8... Nc6 { Now we will see the advance of White's three kingside pawns. } 9. f4
e5
{ 9...Be6  would probably transpose to other lines, but we want to take advantage of White's move order to immediately challenge the center. The point is that White cannot play f5 because they are not castled yet and we would simply take the pawn. }
10. O-O exf4 11. Bxf4 Re8
{ Our d6-pawn is now weak, but so is White's e4-pawn. Our pieces are better prepared for the action as we will see in the next variations. }
12. Qxd6
{ By now White must know that they need to try to equalize, but we're not going to make it so easy for them! }
12... Qb6+
{ Keeping the queens on the board is the best attempt to play for the full point. }
13. Kh1 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Rxe4 15. Bf3 Re6
{ A tiny finesse that forces the queen to retreat to its camp before going all the way down to e8. }
16. Qd2 Re8
{ The rook is not well-placed on e6 because it blocks the way of the light-squared bishop. }
17. c3 { Limiting the action of the bishop on g7. } 17... Ne5
{ 17...Be6  or  17...Bf5  are good moves, of course, but I like this dynamic idea better, as the knight harasses White's bishop and heads towards c4. }
18. Bd5
{ 18.Rae1  doesn't give anything special for White after  18...Bf5  . However, the text could be the best attempt to equalize. }
18... Be6
{ Threatening Rad8 and fighting for the c4-square, which will be occupied by the knight. }
