[White "11) The Aggressive 6.Be2 without O-O"]
[Black "6.Be2 without O-O: 8.Nb3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional approach. With this move, White will normally play in the center, taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.   The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. Be3
{ Here we're going to analyze the lines where White plays with Be2 and Be3 without castling short. This is an aggressive approach whose main difference with f3 is the control of the g4-square. }
7... O-O 8. Nb3 { A knight retreat which hides really aggressive intentions. }
8... Nc6 { Now we will see the advance of White's three kingside pawns. } 9. g4
Be6
{ Both  9...d5  and  9...a5  are playable, but I decided to go for the classical continuation. When the white knight retreats from d4 to b3 it no longer controls the e6-square, which can be occupied by our bishop, clearly improving the little activity it initially had on d7. }
10. f4 Rc8 11. g5 Ne8
{ Against this move order, it is impossible for us to jump to h5 due to f5. }
12. Qd2 Bxc3
{ At this point in the course you will no longer be surprised by this exchange to immediately break White's center. }
13. Qxc3 f5 14. exf5 { If  14.O-O-O  we develop the knight with  14...Ng7  . }
14... Bxf5
{ Black's position is very comfortable, as we have control of the light squares and, besides, the pawns on f4 and g5 are blocked, which makes White's kingside attack more difficult to carry out.   After ...Qd7 and ...Ng7, we'll consolidate our position and we'll be ready to crush our opponent with ideas like ...Bg4 and ...Nf5. }
