[White "11) The Aggressive 6.Be2 without O-O"]
[Black "6.Be2 without O-O: 8.h4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional approach. With this move, White will normally play in the center, taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.   The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. Be3
{ Here we're going to analyze the lines where White plays with Be2 and Be3 without castling short. This is an aggressive approach whose main difference with f3 is the control of the g4-square. }
7... O-O 8. h4
{ The bishop on e2 supports h5, so this move makes a lot of sense. } 8... h5
{ The safest thing to do is not to allow the h-pawn to get too close to the castled king. }
9. Qd2 Nc6 10. O-O-O d5
{ The most consistent thing to do in this position. Without h4 and ...h5 included we would recommend ...Ng4. What's the difference?   After the exchange on g4 and the move f3 by White we can retreat to e6 only when our pawn is on h7 because, in case White captures on e6, the pawn on g6 is not so weak. As we can see, the position is full of subtleties. }
11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Without the moves h4 and ...h5 played, White takes directly on d5, but with them, these trades slightly favor Black. }
13. Bd4 { A standard move aimed at stopping the influence of Black's bishop. }
13... e5 14. Bc5 Bf5
{ A typical exchange sacrifice, although the bishop usually goes to e6. I like this move because it takes advantage of the differences with the lines where White's pawn is on f3 and the bishop on e2. The e4-square is denied to the white knight and g4 is not possible either. }
15. Bc4 { Adding pressure on d5. } 15... Re8
{ A good moment to remove the rook from the bishop's threat. Besides, it makes the ...e4 push more powerful. }
16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. Qxd5
{ White takes a central pawn but some files and diagonals will be open and, therefore, Black has enough compensation for the material. Of course, we're not allowing the queen trade! }
17... Qf6 { 17...Qc7  is a good option too. } 18. Qd6
{ White must seek to eliminate the dangerous black queen! } 18... Rec8
{ The queens may come off the board, but the weakness on the c-file is still there. Let's see how play might continue:   19.Qxf6  Bxf6  20.Rd5  ,  defending the bishops the best way possible.  20...Rc7  ,  preparing to double rooks on the c-file. White has some options, but here we're going to see one of the most forcing ones.  21.b4  ,  supporting the c5-bishop should be a priority.  21...a5  ,  hitting the dike that holds the bishop!  22.b5  Rac8  23.b6  ,  the pawn keeps pushing and pushing.    23...Rc6  24.b7  Rb8  25.Bb5  is forced. The idea is to gain the a6-square for the bishop.  25...Rc7  26.Ba6  Be4  ,  harassing the rook. The bishop also points to b7.  27.Rhd1  Rc6  ,  we want to eliminate the b7-pawn as soon as possible.  28.Bb5  Bxd5  29.Rxd5  Rxc5  30.Rxc5  Rxb7  .  The material is even and, with the presence of the opposite-colored bishops on the board, the most likely result is a draw. }
