{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional approach. With this move, White will normally play in the center, taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.   The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. Be3
{ Here we're going to analyze the lines where White plays with Be2 and Be3 without castling short. This is an aggressive approach whose main difference with f3 is the control of the g4-square. }
7... O-O 8. h4
{ The bishop on e2 supports h5, so this move makes a lot of sense. } 8... h5
{ The safest thing to do is not to allow the h-pawn to get too close to the castled king. }
9. Qd2 Nc6 10. O-O-O d5
{ The most consistent thing to do in this position. Without h4 and ...h5 included we would recommend ...Ng4. What's the difference?   After the exchange on g4 and the move f3 by White, we can retreat to e6 only when our pawn is on h7 because, in case White captures on e6, the pawn on g6 is not so weak. As we can see, the position is full of subtleties. }
11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Without the moves h4 and ...h5 played, White takes directly on d5, but with them, these trades slightly favor Black. }
13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Qxd5 Qc7
{ The key move in these types of positions is to get compensation for the pawn. If White doesn't take the rook, the attack along the b- and c-files would be very unpleasant to face. }
15. Qxa8 Bf5 16. Qxf8+ Kxf8
{ The key to this position is that we are going to play ...Kg8 early so that the king is safe without worrying about back-rank mate ideas, and the action of our queen coordinated with the bishops is very dangerous for White.   When we still have the pawn on h7 we usually have to spend some time playing ...h5 to achieve this. }
17. Bd3
{ The bishop trade will benefit White against the pressure that the castled king is suffering so this move is logical and also prevents the checkmate on c2. }
17... Be6 18. Kb1
{ Defending a2. It's difficult to know if this move is better or worse than a3. }
18... Kg8
{ And as we've mentioned, we put the king closer to the escape hatch. } 19. Bc1
{ The best continuation to face the threat of ...Qb7. } 19... Bf6
{ A fine idea to coordinate the threats on the queenside with the hits on the kingside. Although the position is objectively equal, it is White who will have to play more precisely in order to not be worse. }
