{ The positional approach. With this move, White will normally play in the center, taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.   The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. Be3
{ Here we're going to analyze the lines where White plays with Be2 and Be3 without castling short. This is an aggressive approach whose main difference with f3 is the control of the g4-square. }
7... O-O 8. g4
{ Moves like this one can be scary if we're not well prepared to face them properly. }
8... Nc6
{ 8...d5  is a good alternative, but I want to introduce a novelty that is already almost typical in this course. }
9. g5
{ If  9.h4  we take with  9...Bxg4  , and if @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2np1np1/8/3NP1P1/2N1B3/PPP1BP1P/R2QK2R w KQ - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.f3  we strike with  9...d5  . }
9... Nh5
{ Novelty! This is not the first time that we'll encourage White to take on h5. White should be careful now: we want to jump to f4! }
10. Bxh5 gxh5 11. Qd2 { Now it's time for White to go for castling. } 11... Be6
{ At first, I liked  11...Ne5  but after seeing that White could play  12.O-O-O  without being afraid of ...Nc4, I didn't like that move anymore. }
12. O-O-O Qa5 { Threatening to take on a2. } 13. Kb1 Rfc8
{ The rook is pointing to the c3-knight and threatens to take it in the future with the idea of taking on a2 later on. }
14. a3
{ If White is forced to play this move after playing Kb1, it means that something has gone wrong! }
14... Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bxd4 16. Qxd4 Rc4
{ Followed by ...Rac8 and ...b5, with a ferocious attack. } *

