[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) The Aggressive 6.Be2 without O-O"]
[Black "6.Be2 without O-O: 7.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional approach. With this move, White will normally play in the center, taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.   The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. f4
{ Here we are going to see some lines where White throws a pawn storm without developing almost any pieces! }
7... Nc6 8. Nb3
{ 8.Be3  would transpose to other -and more principled- lines. In this case, White tries to prevent Black's pressure on d4 by retreating the knight. }
8... O-O 9. g4
{ Excessive optimism by White. This was the last opportunity to transpose to the main lines with moves such as  9.Be3  or  9.O-O  . }
9... a5
{ The most dynamic option, intending to harass White's knight immediately. Another good option is  9...e5  to meet the move  10.f5  with  10...d5  , but I rejected this option because after  11.Bg5  ,  we have no better options than trading on e4, getting to an endgame. Are you sure, dear Dragon player, that you want to trade queens this early? }
10. a4 { Only move, otherwise ...a4 by Black would be very strong. } 10... Nb4
{ Hitting c2. The threat is ...Nxg4 so White's next move is practically forced. }
11. g5 Nh5
{ The most aggressive retreat. The knight will be well placed here because we will soon play ...f5, opening the f-file, and we'll coordinate the pieces against f4. }
12. O-O
{ This is apparently the normal move, but it's Black who has the initiative. }
12... Qb6+ { Immediately occupying the fragile g1-a7 diagonal. } 13. Kg2 f5
{ Black's idea is to open the position to make White pay dearly for their excesses. }
14. Nd5
{ The best reply. After the exchange on d5, the f-file will no longer be open. }
14... Nxd5 15. exd5 e5 { We keep on insisting! } 16. dxe6 Bxe6
{ Black has an advantage because all the pieces are better coordinated. The bishops sweep the queenside, next to the queen; the rooks are ready to enter on the c- and e-files while the knight continues its silent pressure on f4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) The Aggressive 6.Be2 without O-O"]
[Black "6.Be2 without O-O: 7.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional approach. With this move, White will normally play in the center, taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.   The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. Bg5 { A rather unknown yet dangerous line! } 7... Nc6 8. Nb3 O-O 9.
Qd2 { White wants to play Bh6 and h4 as soon as possible. } 9... Be6
{ Taking advantage of the square left uncontrolled by White's knight. } 10.
O-O-O { Consequent with White's previous play. } 10... a5
{ Quickly harassing the knight. } 11. a4
{ White cannot allow the advance of the a-pawn. } 11... Rc8
{ Once we can no longer advance the a-pawn, we put the rook on its natural square but having weakened the castle first! Threats like ...Nb4 and ...Nxe4 are strong so White has to take action. }
12. f3 { Supporting e4. } 12... Nd7
{ This move has the idea of taking on b3 followed by ...Nc5. } 13. Bh6
{ Counterpunching! } 13... Bxb3 { The most direct move. } 14. Bxg7
{ 14.cxb3  would be a blunder due to  14...Nd4!  and Black wins. } 14... Kxg7
15. cxb3 Nc5 { Hitting b3. } 16. Bc4 { The only way of defending b3. } 16...
Qb6 { We insist! } 17. Qc2
{ I don't believe that any of your opponents will play  17.Kc2  but, just in case, you can reply  17...Qb4  ,  threatening knight jumps all over the place. }
17... Ne5 { We continue hassling. } 18. Kb1
{ The only thing I don't like about this variation is that against  18.Bb5  I will recommend playing  18...Nc6  ,  threatening ...Nb4, so White returns to c4 with the bishop and your best move would be ...Ne5 - although if you feel like playing for a win, I would recommend ...e6 followed by ...Rfd8. }
18... Nxc4 19. bxc4 Qb3
{ The best move. If White trade queens, there's no attack anymore. } 20. Qxb3
Nxb3 21. Kc2 Nc5 { With a comfortable, although objectively even position. } *

