1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional approach. With this move, White will normally play in the center, taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.   The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. Bg5 { A rather unknown yet dangerous line! } 7... Qa5
{ I recommend playing this move if your opponent is below 2000 ELO rating and is not well prepared. Although you give White an additional option, you will usually transpose to the main line if your opponent plays correctly and, along the way, set a small trap too. }
8. Bd2
{ I'm sure that many of your opponents -especially in blitz- will play  8.Qd2  , a move that loses material after  8...Nxe4! }
8... Nc6 9. Nd5
{ The normal move would be  9.Nb3  ,  which we'll meet with  9...Qd8  and after  10.Be3  or  10.Bg5  we would transpose to the corresponding line. }
9... Qd8 10. Nxf6+
{ I don't think White would gladly go for this trade, but e4 was hanging. }
10... Bxf6 11. Be3
{ Now we have several options but we choose the simplest one to equalize. }
11... Qa5+ 12. c3 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Bxd4 14. Qxd4 O-O
{ Black has a healthy position. Just in case, I analyze the line where White tries to attack us. }
15. h4 Be6 16. h5 Rac8 17. hxg6 fxg6 { Followed by ...Qc5. } *

