1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Be2
{ The positional approach. With this move, White will normally play in the center, taking advantage of the fact that they have more space there.   The games will seem slower at the beginning than the usual ones with opposite castling but they can become very concrete, so we must be well prepared. }
6... Bg7 7. h4 Nc6 8. Be3 h5 9. Qd2
{ 9.f3  O-O  would transpose to a line that we analyze starting with the move7.Be3. Likewise, we could now transpose to the main line by castling, but I'm going to offer you another possibility. }
9... Ng4
{ If White doesn't control this square, let's punish them for not doing it! }
10. Bxg4 Bxg4 11. Nd5
{ With this move, White tries to take advantage of the fact that there's no black knight on f6. The point is to play c4 and build a Maroczy Bind type of structure. }
11... Rc8 12. c4
{ The Maroczy has always been annoying for me to face and, in fact, I like to play it against the Accelerated Dragon. In this case, we're going to react quickly to avoid fighting against this pawn structure for a long time. }
12... Qa5
{ If we trade queens, White will have a lot of problems, so their next move is a must. }
13. b4 Qa4
{ White has a lot of space, but they couldn't support their pawns, as ...Ne5 is coming. Besides, the first player will miss the light-squared bishop being on the board. }
14. O-O Ne5 15. Rac1
{ The idea of this move is to lose the pawn with dignity! White has enough compensation for it, so we should be careful. }
15... Nxc4 16. Qd3
{ Now we have some options, but we choose the one which complicates the game the most. }
16... e6 17. Rxc4 exd5 18. Rxc8+ Bxc8 19. exd5 O-O
{ We have a comfortable position and we can think about fighting for the advantage as soon as we solve the little coordination problem we have at the moment. }
