[White "12) The Solid 6.Bc4 without Be3"]
[Black "6.Bc4 without Be3: 9.h3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Bc4
{ I had hardly paid attention to this move until this year when Dubov and Fedoseev used it in online tournaments. }
6... Bg7
{ In this case  6...Nc6  would be a serious mistake because White can play  7.Nxc6  and follow with e5. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
{ A solid line that which gained some popularity among the more solid players. }
8... Nc6 9. h3 Nxd4
{ In this case, after so much preparation, we decided to displace their queen and continue, in short, to gain tempi. }
10. Qxd4 Bd7 { The bishop heads to c6. } 11. Bg5 h6
{ Where does this bishop go? } 12. Bc1
{ A bit sad, but interesting, to be able to meet ...Ng4 with Qd1. } 12... Bc6
13. Qd3 Nd7
{ Anand played like this against Ljubojevic... in 1998! It's been a long time since then! }
14. Be3 Ne5 15. Qf1 Nxc4 16. Qxc4 Qa5
{ With a healthy position with the bishop pair and few reasons from White to pose problems. Let's look at some ideas. }
17. a4 { Trying to stop our expansion on the queenside. } 17... Rac8 18. Qd3
Bxc3 { Weakening White's pawn structure. } 19. bxc3 Kg7
{ Although difficult to convert into a full point, our position is better. We should play ...f6 to solidify the center and put pressure along the c-file or try to play ...d5 next. }
