[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) The Solid 6.Bc4 without Be3"]
[Black "6.Bc4 without Be3: 9.Nb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Bc4
{ I had hardly paid attention to this move until this year when Dubov and Fedoseev used it in online tournaments. }
6... Bg7
{ In this case  6...Nc6  would be a serious mistake because White can play  7.Nxc6  and follow with e5. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
{ A solid line that which gained some popularity among the more solid players. }
8... Nc6 9. Nb3
{ A solid line that aims to hide the bishop on c1 and put a knight on d5. }
9... Be6
{ 9...Ne5  followed by ...Ng4 is also a perfectly playable alternative. } 10.
Bf1 d5 { Once more, if we can strike in the center, let's do it! } 11. Nc5
{ The most popular move but maybe not the best option! } 11... dxe4 12. Nxe6
fxe6 { We have a nice traffic light on the e-file. } 13. Bc4
{ The most logical move, pointing at Black's weaknesses.  13.Be3  would be met by  13...Qa5  . }
13... Qb6
{ We give the material back immediately in return for seizing the initiative. }
14. Bxe6+ Kh8 15. Rf1 { The pressure on f2 gives few options left for White. }
15... Rad8 16. Qe1 Nd4
{ It's clear who has the initiative in this game, and without even giving anything in return for it! Let's see how the game could continue:   17.Bb3  Qa5  is a great move to bring the queen to the kingside, more concretely, to f5.  18.Be3  ,  intending to trade on d4 in case we play ...Qf5.  18...Ng4  ,  these knights are a nightmare for White!  19.h3  is the only move to keep White in the game.  19...Nf3+  ,  a piece sacrifice to ruin White's castling.  20.gxf3  Ne5  21.Qe2  and White should keep playing only moves in order to not lose on the spot.    21...Nxf3+  22.Kg2  Nh4+  23.Kg1  Qc7  ,  threatening to get back to f3 and penetrate via h2.  24.f4  exf3  25.Qf2  and White has managed to defend, somehow, the kingside.  25...Ng2  26.Bxa7  is another only move.  26...Nf4  27.Kh1  Nxh3  28.Qh2  Nf4  ,  threatening to take on h3.  29.Be3  Rf5  30.Bxf4  Qxf4  31.Qxf4  Rxf4  .  The four passed pawns on the kingside are worth more than the knight and White will still have to fight for a draw. }
