{ A solid line that aims to hide the bishop on c1 and put a knight on d5. }
9... Be6
{ 9...Ne5  followed by ...Ng4 is also a perfectly playable alternative. } 10.
Bf1 d5 { Once more, if we can strike in the center, let's do it! } 11. exd5
Nxd5 { In these types of positions, we are never going to have problems. } 12.
Ne4 Qb6 { Activating the queen and freeing d8 for one of the rooks. } 13. Nbc5
{ Harassing our bishop. } 13... Rad8 { It's all yours! } 14. Nxe6 fxe6
{ White has ruined our pawn structure but, in return, all of our pieces are already in really active spots. To start with, the first player must take measures to avoid the discovered attacks with the d5-knight. }
15. Qg4
{ White removes the queen attacking our weakness, what could go wrong? } 15...
Nd4 { Striking back. We defend e6 and attack c2. } 16. Bd3 Nb4
{ Our knights are doing some damage already. } 17. Be3
{ Practically, the only move to avoid having a huge disadvantage. } 17... Nxd3
18. cxd3 Qxb2 { And, even if the e6-pawn falls, our position is preferable. } *

