[Round "?"]
[White "13) The Unusual 6.Bc4 / 7.Be3 without f3"]
[Black "6.Bc4 / 7.Be3 without f3: 9.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Bc4
{ I had hardly paid attention to this move until this year when Dubov and Fedoseev used it in online tournaments. }
6... Bg7
{ In this case  6...Nc6  would be a serious mistake because White can play  7.Nxc6  and follow with e5. }
7. Be3
{ This position has been played quite a lot, although more usually using the 6.Be3 and 7.Bc4 move order.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  g6  6.Be3  Bg7  7.Bc4  . Black players usually don't punish White for this inaccuracy and simply castle, but here we don't miss any opportunity. We're not that kind of player! }
7... Ng4
{ Taking advantage of the fact that White has 'forgotten' to control this square with f3 or h3. }
8. Bb5+
{ The only way to justify White's move order. Now it is not possible  8...Bd7  due to  9.Qxg4  winning a piece, but Black willingly sacrifices the right of castling. }
8... Kf8 9. O-O Be5
{ A precise move that weakens White's castling pawn structure before taking on e3. The first time I saw it was in the fabulous book Secrets of Chess Training mentioned by the prestigious coach Boris Zlotnik. }
10. Qd2 Bxh2+ { A pawn that flies, to the pot! } 11. Kh1 Be5
{ We don't take on e3 this time because retreating the bishop would easily give us a very good game. }
12. f4
{ The best move intending to save the bishop and going for the black king. }
12... Bg7 13. Rad1
{ If  13.Bg1  we reply the same way with  13...Kg8  ,  transposing to the main line, and there we will explain this mysterious move! }
13... Kg8
{ How strange this move seems! The idea is deep, play ...Qf8, and try to bring it to h6. }
14. Bg1
{ What a relief the bishop feels as it moves out of the knight's range! } 14...
Nc6 { No time to lose! } 15. Bxc6
{ White's idea is to take with the knight on c6 and continue with Nd5. } 15...
Qf8 { Brilliant! The queen goes to h6 at full speed. } 16. Ba4
{ The retreat is quite similar. } 16... Bxd4 { Threatening ...Qh6. } 17. Rf3
Bxg1 18. Kxg1 Qd8
{ Hoping for b6 to continue frightening the White king. We have a very double-edged position with attacking chances for both sides. Let's see how play might continue:   19.Qd4  ,  preventing Black's idea.  19...Bd7  20.Bxd7  Qxd7  21.e5  ,  trying to punish Black's lack of coordination.  21...Rc8  ,  we remind you once again of the importance of fighting for the initiative in the Dragon!  22.Qxa7   22.exd6  ,  getting the pawn back directly is not the most advisable thing to do.  22...Qxd6  23.Qxd6  exd6  24.Rxd6  .  It would seem to be a comfortable ending for White, but, in fact, they must be careful not to be worse!  24...Kg7  25.Rd7  Rhd8  26.Rfd3  Rxd7  27.Rxd7  b5  ,  intending to enter on c2.  28.Nxb5  Rxc2  and we enter on the 7th rank threatening mate.  29.g3  Rxb2  30.Nd6  Rxa2  31.Nxf7  and White has equalized, although struggling to do so.  22...Qf5  ,  bringing the queen close to the attack.  23.Qxb7  Kg7  24.Qxe7  Qxc2  ,  threatening ...Rxc3 followed by ...Qxd1.  25.Re1  Qxb2  26.e6  Rxc3  27.Qxf7+  Kh6  28.Qe7  Rxf3  29.Qg5+  Kg7  30.Qe7+  and White guarantees the perpetual check after  30...Kh6  . }
