1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Bc4
{ I had hardly paid attention to this move until this year when Dubov and Fedoseev used it in online tournaments. }
6... Bg7
{ In this case  6...Nc6  would be a serious mistake because White can play  7.Nxc6  and follow with e5. }
7. Be3
{ This position has been played quite a lot, although more usually using the 6.Be3 and 7.Bc4 move order.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  g6  6.Be3  Bg7  7.Bc4  . Black players usually don't punish White for this inaccuracy and simply castle, but here we don't miss any opportunity. We're not that kind of player! }
7... Ng4
{ Taking advantage of the fact that White has 'forgotten' to control this square with f3 or h3. }
8. Bb5+
{ The only way to justify White's move order. Now it is not possible  8...Bd7  due to  9.Qxg4  winning a piece, but Black willingly sacrifices the right of castling. }
8... Kf8 9. Bg5
{ The attempt to escape from the dark horse's hooves is logical but ineffective. }
9... h6 10. Bh4 Qb6
{ Immediately taking advantage of the absence of the white bishop on important diagonals while hitting the bishop on b5. White is already in serious trouble. }
11. Bxe7+
{ The only resource that at first sight may seem effective. We cannot take the bishop due to the fork on d5. }
11... Kg8 12. Nd5
{ The most forced continuation, but it leads to nothing good for White. } 12...
Qxd4 13. Qxd4 Bxd4 14. Nc7 a6 15. Nxa8 axb5
{ White has rook and pawn for the two pieces but now faces some problems because we are threatening to take on b2 and on f2. The only way not to lose material goes as follows:   16.f3  Ne3  17.c3  Be5  and White has managed, with two modest pawn steps, to keep the material balance and slow down Black's initiative to some extent. However, having a comfortable game is still a long way off.   We threaten the fork on c2 and ...Nc4 as well, hitting b2. White can still reduce the damage with precise play.  18.Nb6  is a nice in-between move, attacking the bishop.  18...Be6  19.Kf2  ,  preventing the fork and defending g2.  19...Nc6  ,  we continue developing while creating threats. If White retreats the bishop, we simply play ...Nc4 and recapture on c4 with the pawn. After ...Ra8 and the advance of the b-pawn, White's position would be close to collapse.   For that reason, it is better to let the white bishop fall, but then the power of the bishop pair will be felt. Let's go even deeper to understand this endgame.  20.Kxe3  Nxe7  21.f4  ,  harassing the bishop to hit quickly on d6.  21...Bf6  is a much better retreat than Bg7, as this square will be taken by Black's king.  22.Rhd1  Nc6  is the most precise move. White can take on d6, but we will get the material back due to the fact that the b6-knight is hanging.    23.Rxd6  Be7  24.Rd5  ,  White should prevent ...Bc5.  24...b4  25.Rb5  Na7  26.Rxb4  Bc5+  is a very instructive intermezzo that worsens White's king situation.  27.Kf3  Bxb4  28.cxb4  Kg7  29.Rc1  Rd8  and we will soon see how deep the check we gave on c5 is.  30.Rc7  Rd3+  ,  removing the king from the 3rd rank.  31.Ke2  Rd4  ,  hitting both pawns. Winning the game is now easy! }
