[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Levenfish Variation (6.f4)"]
[Black "Levenfish Variation: 7.Nxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. f4
{ The Levenfish Variation, named after Grandmaster Grigori Levenfish, one of the best Soviet players of the early 20th century.  This variation was very popular at the amateur level in the 90s because of the difficulties that Black faces if they play the natural  6...Bg7  after  7.e5!  .    It's worth pointing out that this is one of the first variations that is taught to Beth Harmon in the popular Netflix series The Queen's Gambit. }
6... Nc6
{ The most precise move. Black fights directly for the center and controls the opponent's king pawn push. }
7. Nxc6
{ One of the things I like most about playing this line with Black is that White usually replies with this move! It is by far the most popular move, but certainly the worst of the possible alternatives for White.  White insists on the idea to break on e5 before either player completes their development. }
7... bxc6 8. e5 Nd7
{ The only reasonable square for the knight. I know, dear user; it may seem that White is taking the initiative and Black's pieces are a bit strange, but isn't this what hypermodern chess is all about?  White has overexpanded and the pieces are not in time to keep up with the initiative of the pawns. }
9. exd6 exd6 10. Be3 Be7 11. Qd2 O-O 12. O-O-O d5
{ Reaching a type of position that you will already be familiar with. Black has a strong center and is prepared to coordinate their pieces on the queenside with ...Rb8, ...Qa5, ...Bf6, and the entry of the knight via b6-c4 or c5. }
13. h4 { The most natural try. Let's have a look at how to face it. } 13... Nf6
{ Improving the knight and controlling the h5-square. } 14. Be2 { Insisting. }
14... Ng4
{ 14...h5  would also be possible and good, but this move is instructive because you should take the e3-bishop whenever possible! }
15. h5
{ If  15.Bd4  Black will follow with  15...c5  and if  15.Bg1  we can calmly take  on h4. Have you ever seen a Dragon player afraid? }
15... Nxe3 16. Qxe3 Bf6
{ Another instructive position. With the Dragon's bishop safe we will 'never' get mated! Note that even if the h-file is opened and the queen gets to h2, with the simple ...Re8 we would give an escape square to the black king that will be very comfortable.   It is important to repeat that the tranquility comes from having captured the bishop on e3 and also there are no knight jumps... Unfortunately, we are not always going to have such good positions, so enjoy it! }
*

