[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Levenfish Variation (6.f4)"]
[Black "Levenfish Variation: 7.Nxc6 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. f4
{ The Levenfish Variation, named after Grandmaster Grigori Levenfish, one of the best Soviet players of the early 20th century.  This variation was very popular at the amateur level in the 90s because of the difficulties that Black faces if they play the natural  6...Bg7  after  7.e5!  .    It's worth pointing out that this is one of the first variations that is taught to Beth Harmon in the popular Netflix series The Queen's Gambit. }
6... Nc6
{ The most precise move. Black fights directly for the center and controls the opponent's king pawn push. }
7. Nxc6
{ One of the things I like most about playing this line with Black is that White usually replies with this move! It is by far the most popular move, but certainly the worst of the possible alternatives for White.  White insists on the idea to break on e5 before either player completes their development. }
7... bxc6 8. e5 Nd7
{ The only reasonable square for the knight. I know, dear user; it may seem that White is taking the initiative and Black's pieces are a bit strange, but isn't this what hypermodern chess is all about?  White has overexpanded and the pieces are not in time to keep up with the initiative of the pawns. }
9. Qf3
{ This move can be scary if you don't know the theory, but to avoid this you bought this Chessable course, right? }
9... Bg7 { The c6-pawn is all yours! Black's initiative will be very strong. }
10. Qxc6 Rb8 11. Be3
{ The best move, inviting Black to take on b2. Holding on to the material with  11.exd6  would only bring problems after Black castles. }
11... Rxb2
{ 11...O-O  is easier to play, but I trust you will remember all the theory, as accepting the invitation is clearly more fun! }
12. Nb5
{ This is White's idea. The threat is giving a check on c7 and, at the same time, this move leaves Black's rook with no squares to go to. }
12... O-O 13. Qc3 Rxb5
{ Sacrificing an exchange, even if in this case it is forced, is something that is in the DNA of every Dragon player. }
14. Bxb5 dxe5 15. O-O-O
{ White could not recapture on e5 because after ...Bxe5, they will lose material. I leave it to the attentive user to choose the winning variation after Bd4; the white king is too exposed in the center! }
15... exf4 16. Bd4 e5
{ Arriving at a position as complex as beautiful to play. Let's see a game played by email between two very strong opponents:   17.Bxa7  e4  18.Bd4  Bxd4  19.Qxd4  .  Is the pin annoying?  19...Qg5  ,  not at all!  20.Bxd7  f3+  21.Kb1  Bxd7  22.Qxd7  Rb8+  23.Ka1  f2  .  The pawns and the bad position of White's king compensate for the rook.  24.h4  Qg3  25.Qd4  e3  26.h5  ½-½ @@StartBracket@@26@@EndBracket@@ Alonso González, C. @@StartBracket@@2425@@EndBracket@@ - González Rabago, N. @@StartBracket@@2455@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email, 2015. }
