[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Levenfish Variation (6.f4)"]
[Black "Levenfish Variation: 7.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. f4
{ The Levenfish Variation, named after Grandmaster Grigori Levenfish, one of the best Soviet players of the early 20th century.  This variation was very popular at the amateur level in the 90s because of the difficulties that Black faces if they play the natural  6...Bg7  after  7.e5!  .    It's worth pointing out that this is one of the first variations that is taught to Beth Harmon in the popular Netflix series The Queen's Gambit. }
6... Nc6
{ The most precise move. Black fights directly for the center and controls the opponent's king pawn push. }
7. Nf3
{ A less direct but more correct continuation. The great Judit Polgar achieved a good victory in '96 against Topalov. Let's see how to improve Veselin's game! }
7... Bg7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O
{ White plans to play Qe1 to bring it to h4 and harass Black's king. It is important to remember the following move that 'steals' the initiative from White. }
9... b5
{ Whenever the white king is on g1 and the f-pawn is pushed, remember to look at this type of move. The g1-a7 diagonal often creates discomfort for White. }
10. Nxb5
{ It is interesting that there are only five games in the database with this position and three of them are by the German GM Feygin, who won all three! If you ever face him, send him a greeting from me after playing this recipe. }
10... Qb6+ 11. Kh1 Nxe4 12. Nxa7 { White is happy capturing a pawn. } 12... Nc5
{ Surprisingly, Black has not tried this very natural move. White's bishop is the target. }
13. Nxc8 Rfxc8
{ The pressure on the queenside more than compensates for being a pawn down, but let's go deeper to better understand the position. }
14. Bc4
{ Saving the bishop seems essential to avoid falling into a position that is too ugly. }
14... e6 { This move limits the bishop and prepares ...d5. } 15. Qe2 Qb7
{ A move that demonstrates the marvelous depth of today's engine analysis. White has a hard time finding a useful move as both  16.c3  and  16.Be3  will be met by  16...Na5  . }
16. Bb5 Nb4
{ It is also possible to play  16...Na7  , which possibly leads to repetition, but we like to play for a win! The threat is ...Nxc2 so White must defend the bishop. }
