[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Levenfish Variation (6.f4)"]
[Black "Levenfish Variation: 7.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. f4
{ The Levenfish Variation, named after Grandmaster Grigori Levenfish, one of the best Soviet players of the early 20th century.  This variation was very popular at the amateur level in the 90s because of the difficulties that Black faces if they play the natural  6...Bg7  after  7.e5!  .    It's worth pointing out that this is one of the first variations that is taught to Beth Harmon in the popular Netflix series The Queen's Gambit. }
6... Nc6
{ The most precise move. Black fights directly for the center and controls the opponent's king pawn push. }
7. Be2
{ This move, in most cases, will not have its own personality because it will transpose to the classical lines. Here we will only analyze the deviations where White plays without Be3. I already tell you that it is not very advisable... }
7... Bg7 { 7...Nxd4  is also perfectly playable. } 8. Nb3 O-O 9. g4
{ 9.O-O  would be met with the thematic  9...b5  while  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2np1np1/8/4PP2/1NN5/PPP1B1PP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Be3  transposes to lines that we will see later. }
9... b5
{ I must admit that I was going to recommend  9...a5  10.a4  e5!  which gives very interesting play for Black. However, going over the line I found this suggestion from Stockfish 12, which gives very dynamic play for the pawn. It is just the kind of position I want you to learn to appreciate... and even love! }
10. g5 Nd7
{ Now White can @@StartBracket@@and should@@EndBracket@@ take on b5 without allowing Black to get the pawn back. However, the king will remain really exposed. }
11. Bxb5 Qb6
{ Immediately taking advantage of the weakness of the dark squares. } 12. Qe2
{ Will White be in time to play Be3? } 12... Rb8 { Threatening ...Bxc3+. } 13.
Bc4 Nd4 { Black continues developing the initiative on the queenside. } 14.
Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Nd5 { Only move to relieve the pressure. } 15... Qd8 16. c3 Bg7
17. Be3
{ A very instructive position. It seems that the worst is over for White and they will emerge from the opening with a healthy extra pawn... but it is not so!   The first player will continue to suffer on the queenside and, as so often happens, to destabilize a position we need the pawns to do their job. }
17... e6 { We start by expelling White's best piece. } 18. Nb4 Qc7
{ Avoiding the fork on c6, putting pressure on the c4-bishop, and eyeing at a possible tickle on c3. }
19. O-O a5 20. Na6
{ The knight has no good squares left, so White is happy to exchange it for the bishop on c8. }
20... Bxa6 21. Bxa6 Nc5
{ Hitting a6 and e4. If Bd3 Black trades on d3 and then b2 will fall, so White should sadly give up their dark-squared bishop. }
22. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 23. Kg2 a4
{ With a very good position for Black, who has fixed White's weaknesses on the queenside and can then try to break with ...d5-d4 or even harass the kingside. }
