1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. f4
{ The Levenfish Variation, named after Grandmaster Grigori Levenfish, one of the best Soviet players of the early 20th century.  This variation was very popular at the amateur level in the 90s because of the difficulties that Black faces if they play the natural  6...Bg7  after  7.e5!  .    It's worth pointing out that this is one of the first variations that is taught to Beth Harmon in the popular Netflix series The Queen's Gambit. }
6... Nc6
{ The most precise move. Black fights directly for the center and controls the opponent's king pawn push. }
7. Be3
{ This move order can't be good... We could omit it with the move  7...Bg7  ,  but I offer you the possibility to try to punish White right away. }
7... Ng4
{ Hitting the bishop on e3 with ...Ng4 is one of the hobbies of Dragon players. Unfortunately, our opponents usually prevent this jump with f3 or h3 the vast majority of the time. }
8. Bg1 e5
{ Very concrete. In this way, the e5-square will be taken for the knights, although, of course, there is the risk that the d6-pawn could be in trouble. }
9. fxe5 Ngxe5 10. Qd2
{ White must quickly go for long castling and dream of putting pressure on d6. }
10... Bg7 11. O-O-O O-O
{ More than for its theoretical value @@StartBracket@@which is quite low because nobody is going to play f4 followed by Be3@@EndBracket@@, I wanted to discuss this position to help you understand these kinds of positions.   Is d6 so weak? Can it be easily attacked? The key is that Black is always going to find good counterplay if White captures the pawn. It is especially worth mentioning the coordination of all the pieces with the bishop on g7: this piece is the conductor of the orchestra! }
12. Ndb5
{ The most direct move, though perhaps not the most accurate.  12.Kb1  is the move recommended by the machine. After the exchange on d4 and ...Be6, Black has a good position. }
12... Be6 { Getting the pieces out. } 13. Nxd6
{ Against  13.Qxd6  the move  13...Qh4  is very strong. We can continue by bringing one of our rooks to d8. }
13... Qb8
{ Preparing ...Rd8.  13...Qa5  is also playable, but it would imply sacrificing the b7-pawn. I prefer not to give so much material away for now. }
14. Ndb5 { Better run away than get pinned. } 14... a6 15. Nd4 Rd8
{ Are you sure you could prevent the pin? } 16. Qe1
{ This is the moment to retreat. Now Black forces a very favorable simplification. }
16... Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Nd3+ 18. Rxd3 Rxd4 19. Rxd4 Bxd4
{ We have reached a position where White has an extra pawn... but is practically lost! The dark squares, especially when the queen gets to e5, are going to be a nightmare.   We will then push on the queenside to create weaknesses in White's castling and the rook will enter at the right moment.   White, meanwhile, has hardly any plans or any way to resist the draconian monologue. A dream position that hopefully one of us will reach in one of our games. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Fianchetto Variation (6.g3)"]
[Black "Fianchetto Variation: 7. Nde2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. g3
{ The Fianchetto Variation has much more venom than it may seem at the amateur level at first glance.   White has an easy plan to follow which consists of playing Nd5, restraining the bishop on g7 with c3, or with a curious plan with a4 and Ra2 to follow later with b3 and c4.   It is certainly a very recommendable line for the White players who want to escape theoretical lines since Black is not usually so well prepared and it is very easy to get worse.   As you can imagine, this is not going to be our case! I will show you a very concrete idea to fight for the initiative from the first moment. That's why we play the Dragon! }
6... Nc6
{ This move quickly makes White uncomfortable if they are not prepared to defend the knight with Be3. However, they must make a decision. }
7. Nde2
{ Preventing the exchange on d4. The knight is not badly placed on e2, from where it has two routes to go to d5. }
7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O
{ It took me a long time to decide which line to recommend, but I finally decided on the main one because it seems to me that it achieves good and risk-free positions.  Ideas such as  8...Bd7  followed by ...Qc8 seem to me very playable as well. }
9. O-O Rb8 { Intending ...b5, which is now unstoppable. } 10. a4
{ It is in White's interest to open the a-file, which will happen after Black's ...a6 and ...b5, so it makes no sense to allow playing ...b5 without preventing it even a little bit.   We will analyze the other options to be accurate in the theoretical sense of the word, but we can also summarize it as they are like the main line but worse for White. }
10... a6 11. Nd5 b5 12. axb5 Rxb5
{ Out of 156 games I have in the database, only one game between a 2008 and a 1968 FIDE players @@StartBracket@@Straka@@EndBracket@@ Black took with the rook.   I think this 'novelty' is very effective, as it will catch your opponents by surprise and, besides, Black's play is very simple. }
13. c3 { A usual move to fight against Black's pressure on b2. } 13... e6 14.
Nxf6+
{ 14.Ne3  would be met, as in other instances, with  14...Qc7  followed by ...Rd8 and ...Bb7, when we are sure that we don't leave our b5-rook trapped. }
14... Bxf6 { Forced. Black's queen has to defend d6. } 15. Bh6
{ Taking advantage of the fact that Black's bishop has left its home. } 15...
Bg7
{ 15...Re8  is also playable, but my intention is playing always against  the g2-bishop that, paradoxically, is the bad one. }
16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Nd4
{ We should analyze this move because, as we have seen, it is typical in these kinds of positions. }
17... Nxd4 18. Qxd4+ e5 { And our reply is also typical! } 19. Qd2 Rb3
{ A precise move to prevent White from removing the weakness on b2 by playing with b4. }
20. Bf3 { With the idea of expelling the rook with Bd1 intending b4. } 20... a5
{ Preventing White's b4. Although the position is objectively equal, however, we are the ones who have the board under our control. }
