[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Fianchetto Variation (6.g3)"]
[Black "Fianchetto Variation: 7. Nde2 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. g3
{ The Fianchetto Variation has much more venom than it may seem at the amateur level at first glance.   White has an easy plan to follow which consists of playing Nd5, restraining the bishop on g7 with c3, or with a curious plan with a4 and Ra2 to follow later with b3 and c4.   It is certainly a very recommendable line for the White players who want to escape theoretical lines since Black is not usually so well prepared and it is very easy to get worse.   As you can imagine, this is not going to be our case! I will show you a very concrete idea to fight for the initiative from the first moment. That's why we play the Dragon! }
6... Nc6
{ This move quickly makes White uncomfortable if they are not prepared to defend the knight with Be3. However, they must make a decision. }
7. Nde2
{ Preventing the exchange on d4. The knight is not badly placed on e2, from where it has two routes to go to d5. }
7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O
{ It took me a long time to decide which line to recommend, but I finally decided on the main one because it seems to me that it achieves good and risk-free positions.  Ideas such as  8...Bd7  followed by ...Qc8 seem to me very playable as well. }
9. O-O Rb8 { Intending ...b5, which is now unstoppable. } 10. a4
{ It is in White's interest to open the a-file, which will happen after Black's ...a6 and ...b5, so it makes no sense to allow playing ...b5 without preventing it even a little bit.   We will analyze the other options to be accurate in the theoretical sense of the word, but we can also summarize it as they are like the main line but worse for White. }
10... a6 11. Nd5 b5 12. axb5 Rxb5
{ Out of 156 games I have in the database, only one game between a 2008 and a 1968 FIDE players @@StartBracket@@Straka@@EndBracket@@ Black took with the rook.   I think this 'novelty' is very effective, as it will catch your opponents by surprise and, besides, Black's play is very simple. }
13. Ra3
{ Retreating the rook with the idea of playing b3 without surprises on the long diagonal. }
13... Nd7 { Hitting b2. } 14. b3 Rb8
{ We retreat the rook before it's attacked, either with c4 or with the arrival of a knight to c3. The idea is to add flexibility to our moves. }
15. Be3
{ Once Black's knight has moved away from f6, we must always keep an eye on this move since we don't have ...Ng4 to harass the bishop. We can't have everything! }
15... e6
{ Let's remind the reader that e3 was the favorite square of the d5-knight. }
16. Ndc3 Qc7
{ An ideal square for the queen, as it supports the d6-point and says 'Hi!' in the distance to the c3-knight. }
17. Qd2 { Avoiding problems on c3 and freeing d1 for the rook. } 17... a5
{ A theoretical and useful move in these structures. The pawn is well-defended on a5, Black wins some space on the queenside and, last but not least, frees the a6-square for Black's light-squared bishop. Now that our development is about to be complete, let's see how play could continue:   18.Rd1  Rd8  − not having studied it at home, you may have been scared when you got to this position. Do you see why buying this course was a good idea?  19.Bg5  ,  messing up a bit Black's healthy setup. Taking on d6 is not possible because, after the trade, the move ...Bf8 would come, winning an exchange. How clumsy the rook on a3 is!  19...Bf6  ,  there are other moves but it seems to me that exchanging bishops is the most recommended way of playing for a win.  20.Bxf6  Nxf6  21.Nd4  Nxd4  22.Qxd4  e5  − not afraid to leave the d5-square as the initiative is ours.  23.Qc4   23.Qd3  Be6  24.Nb5  ,  your opponent may show signs of satisfaction when making this move, but with precise play, we will put them in trouble!  24...Qb6  25.c4  Bd7  ,  engine precision!  26.Nc3  ,  it's not possible to take on d6 with the knight due to ...Bg4 and the house falls.  26...Bc6  ,  controlling d5 and, at the same time, eyeing at e4.  27.Rda1  − in case you are wondering, although it should be clear to you, if the white knight arrives on d5 we capture it with the bishop and then give our opponent a class of good knight, established on c5, against bad bishop.  27...Qb4  ,  overprotecting d6 to be able to play ...Nd7 and bring the knight to c5.  28.Bh3  ,  White has also studied Dvoretsky's material so prevents the knight's maneuver.  28...h5  is a move that gains a bit of space and can be useful to be able to play with h4 perhaps after ...Kg7 and ...Rh8, and even follow-up plans involving moves like ...Nh7-g5. The position is balanced but it is definitely easier for Black to be the one squeezing in the end.  23...Qxc4  24.bxc4  Rb2  25.Rd2  Be6  and the position is even. }
