[White "15) Fianchetto Variation (6.g3)"]
[Black "Fianchetto Variation: 7. Bg2 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. g3
{ The Fianchetto Variation has much more venom than it may seem at the amateur level at first glance.   White has an easy plan to follow which consists of playing Nd5, restraining the bishop on g7 with c3, or with a curious plan with a4 and Ra2 to follow later with b3 and c4.   It is certainly a very recommendable line for the White players who want to escape theoretical lines since Black is not usually so well prepared and it is very easy to get worse.   As you can imagine, this is not going to be our case! I will show you a very concrete idea to fight for the initiative from the first moment. That's why we play the Dragon! }
6... Nc6
{ This move quickly makes White uncomfortable if they are not prepared to defend the knight with Be3. However, they must make a decision. }
7. Bg2
{ I find it hard to understand that this move is as popular as the dangerous  7.Nde2  ,  as it allows Black to have such a comfortable game. In any case, after studying the lines that will follow, you won't be able to avoid a slight inner smile when this situation appears on the board. }
7... Nxd4
{ Of course, we take advantage of the opportunity to trade on d4 and leave White's queen in a bad position. }
8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. a4
{ White tries to gain space on the queenside without defining the rest of the pieces. The idea is clever because the b7-pawn is Black's biggest weakness. }
10... Bd7 { The most flexible reply. } 11. a5 { Following the plan. } 11... Ng4
{ An apparently dubious move. } 12. Qb4
{ We could think that Black is in trouble, but... we give up the b7-pawn! }
12... Rc8
{ I am eternally grateful for all that modern engines teach us. This positional pawn sacrifice is going to lead Black to control the position. }
13. Qxb7 Rc7 { Expelling White's queen from its active position. } 14. Qb4 Bxc3
{ Engines have no complexes! } 15. bxc3 a6
{ Forgive me, dear reader, for not having explained what was going on at this point, but I wanted to have the position in front of us to do it! Black has just given up the Dragon's sacred bishop and then made a quiet pawn push! Black's idea is to fix White's structure on dark squares. Especially important is to keep the grand diagonal closed.   With ...a6, two objectives are achieved: first the a-pawn to continue advancing and fix the pawn on a7, where it would be a weakness easily attacked by the e3-bishop, and second, it supports the arrival of the bishop on b5 from where it does a lot of damage.   Black's queen will be placed on c8, obviously putting pressure on c3, but it can also coordinate with the bishop to enter h3, especially if the pawn advances to harass the knight.   Always enjoy these positions, play with the pieces, don't exchange rooks and if you have to make a break, make sure it is well justified; otherwise, the bishop pair could become noticeable.   When you win your games, recommend this course to a friend and then write to me at divis@chess24.com and I will be glad to hear that you enjoyed it. }
