10... Bd7 { The most flexible reply. } 11. Qb4
{ Logical, trying to take advantage of the fact that b7 is unprotected. } 11...
b6
{ Of course,  11...Bc6  would be a very normal move, but I want to show you that Black doesn't suffer at all because we have the b- and c-files available. }
12. a5 bxa5 13. Qxa5 Ng4
{ Opening the long diagonal. This move implies an exchange sacrifice that should be accepted if White still wants to fight for something tangible. }
14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. e5 Nxe5 16. Bxa8 Rxa8
{ How to evaluate this position? Black has the bishop pair and a pawn for the exchange. Normally, in an open position, this is enough compensation for an exchange. Besides, in this case, we have to add the weaknesses of the light squares around White's king and the fact that Black's pieces are well coordinated. }
17. Nd5
{ The only move that guarantees equality. White threatens both taking on e7 and the very strong move Nb6 so Black's reply is forced. }
17... Bh3 18. f4 { Forced.  18.Rd1  would be met by the annoying  18...Bg4  . }
18... Bxf1 19. Kxf1 Nc4
{ 19...Nc6  is not possible due to  20.Ra6  and the knight cannot be defended with ...Rc8 due to a little combination that I let you solve by yourself. This course is not only about learning Divis' lines by heart! }
20. Nxe7+ Kf8 { With a draw in a few moves. } *

