{ I find it hard to understand that this move is as popular as the dangerous  7.Nde2  ,  as it allows Black to have such a comfortable game. In any case, after studying the lines that will follow, you won't be able to avoid a slight inner smile when this situation appears on the board. }
7... Nxd4
{ Of course, we take advantage of the opportunity to trade on d4 and leave White's queen in a bad position. }
8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. e5
{ The favorite move of the strong GM Onischuk, who has scored 9 points in 10 games with this move and against several 2600+ opponents such as Duda, Jones, Nielsen and Miroshnichenko. So, it will have to be taken seriously! }
9... Nd7
{ I should say that  9...Ng4  10.f4  Nh6  is perfectly playable, but I think that  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/4P3/3Q4/2N3P1/PPP2PBP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nd7  gives White more chances to fall into our preparation. }
10. Qa4 { Nice move, unpinning while pinning. } 10... O-O
{ Giving priority to development over material. In case of  10...Bxe5  White replies with  11.Bh6  ,  preventing Black from castling. The position is still very playable but does not fit the style in which I want you to play the Dragon. }
11. exd6 Nb6 { An intermediate move to fight for the initiative. } 12. Qf4
{ The queen is comfortable on f4 as Black's pieces cannot harass it for the time being. }
12... exd6
{ 12...Qxd6  equalizes without much trouble. However, I won't be tired to repeat that we don't play this opening for a draw! }
13. O-O Be6
{ Supporting White's knight jump to c4 while freeing the c8-square for the rook. Now White has several alternatives depending on whether they prefer to go for the b7-pawn or the d6-pawn. }
14. Rd1
{ Logical, hitting d6.  14.Bxb7  is not advisable because after  14...Rb8  15.Bg2  Nc4  ,  Black will quickly get the pawn back. }
14... Nc4
{ This strong knight not only hits b2 but also defends c4! What a colt! } 15.
Rb1
{ An ugly move, but maybe necessary to try to slow down Black's initiative. }
15... Rc8
{ By now you should be familiar with Black's piece configuration. The position is complex and that is why I have decided to go deeper into it. }
16. Bxb7 g5
{ Again playing for a win.  16...Rb8  leads to a forced draw after  17.Bd5  Bxd5  18.Nxd5  and the knight attacks the rook forever with ...Na3 and ...Nc2. }
17. Qf3
{ The most natural square as  17.Qe4  swould be met by  17...Re8  and White's queen will be forced to move again. }
17... h6
{ Did you think I was going to recommend removing the rook? With this exchange sacrifice, Black wants to gain control over the light squares and I don't think many players would feel comfortable playing this position as White. }
18. Bxc8
{ Critical. Another option would be to strike with  18.h4  but after  18...Ne5  Black is fine. }
18... Qxc8 19. Nd5 { Improving the knight while threatening a fork on e7. }
19... Re8 20. Nf6+
{ White should not miss the opportunity to grab the powerful bishop on g7. }
20... Bxf6 21. Qxf6 Ne5
{ Intending ...Bg4. White is fortunate to have a sacrifice that gives them a good chance of opening the game. }
22. Bxg5 hxg5 23. Rxd6 { And to avoid the perpetual, Black should play: } 23...
Bf5 24. Qxg5+ Bg6
{ Reaching a position that objectively is even, but I still prefer playing with Black. }
*

