1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Bd3
{ A very unusual move that has the advantage of overprotecting e4, but in return, d4 is weaker because the queen doesn't protect the knight anymore. }
6... Nc6 { Directly hitting d4. } 7. Nxc6
{ The best option at this point in time, since if  7.Be3  we would play  7...Ng4  and if @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp2pp1p/2np1np1/8/4P1b1/2NB1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq -@@EndFEN@@  7.Nf3  Bg4  . }
7... bxc6 8. O-O Bg7
{ Now White should choose how they want to play, but they won't cause us any problems because our c6-pawn supports the center, controls the important d5-square, and also the b-file is available for our rook. }
9. b3
{ The fianchetto on the queenside is not something usually seen against the Dragon; but precisely in this variation, since there are no ...Nxe4 ideas, it is possible. }
9... Nd7 10. Bb2 Qa5
{ Asking White what they want to do about the long diagonal. } 11. Na4
{ 11.Qd2  would be met with  11...Nc5  ,  harassing the other bishop. } 11...
O-O 12. Bxg7 Kxg7
{ The position is more or less even, but it will be good for us to know some plans to play in similar situations. }
13. f4 Nb6
{ I like this idea better than  13...Nc5  because the a-file could be more useful for us than the b-file once White has played b3. }
14. Nxb6
{ If the knight retreats to b2 then ...Qc3 would be quite uncomfortable. }
14... axb6 15. a4
{ Preventing us from putting a piece on a3, which would leave a permanent weakness on a2. Now we can think, in the long run, about looking for the ...b5 break, but first, let's gain some space in the center! }
15... e5
{ The idea of this move is to fix the weakness on e4 and then we would consider playing without ...Ba6 because we will have a good bishop. Our queen will arrive at e5 and, in case we are offered the exchange of queens, we will leave it on e5 so that our pawn gets there and then the f5-pawn will join. }
