1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Bb5+ Bd7
7. Bxd7+
{ 7.Qe2  is a move that is usually seen but does not give much to White after  7...Nc6  . }
7... Nbxd7 8. O-O Bg7 9. Be3
{ Can someone explain to me what did White get from the bishop exchange? } 9...
O-O 10. f4 { Moves such as  10.Qd2  are simply met by  10...Ne5  . } 10... Rc8
11. Qf3 { White's pseudoactive attempt. } 11... Nb6
{ We manage to bring the knight to c4 by another way. } 12. Rad1
{ Some players have tried  12.Ndb5  ,  intending to avoid  12...Nc4  ,  but in fact, they don't make it because it'll not be possible to play  13.Bxa7  due to the fork on d2. }
12... Nc4 13. Bc1 Qb6 { Threatening ...e5. } 14. Na4
{ The only way of expelling the queen from b6. } 14... Qb4 15. b3 e5
{ The point! We get the e5-square for the knight, which gives us an advantage. }
