1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Bb5+ Bd7
7. O-O Bg7 8. Be2
{ The best move, losing a tempo but with the bishop on d7 there's no ...d5 break. If  8.Be3  O-O  White will not have any interesting option to keep the variation independent, and therefore they will transpose to7.Bxd7 or to Be2  -the variation that will be analyzed here. }
8... O-O 9. Be3 Nc6 10. f4
{ This is a good version of the lines with f4 and the bishop on c8. There is only one line where White can try to justify that the bishop is worse on d7 than on c8. }
10... Qb6 { Taking advantage of the fact that the diagonal is weak. } 11. Qd3
{ Preventing e4 shenanigans. } 11... Qxb2 12. Rab1
{ Now b7 is undefended - note that the bishop is on d7. } 12... Qa3 13. Rxb7
Rfc8
{ Putting pressure on c3. To be fair, White has the option to follow a long line to defend an endgame with a pawn up to get to a draw. Let's see it. }
14. Nd5 { Forcing the queen trade. } 14... Qxd3 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bxd3 Nxd4
17. Rxd7 Nxc2 18. Bxc2 Rxc2
{ We gain a pawn but White can still force more exchanges. Let's see how the game could continue:   19.e5  dxe5  20.fxe5  Bxe5  21.Rxe7  and there's no way for Black to get an advantage here.  21...f6  22.Rd1  Rc7  23.Rxc7  Bxc7  24.Rd7  Bb6  25.Bxb6  axb6  26.Rd6  Kf7  27.Rxb6  Rxa2  .  This endgame is a draw. }
*

