1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Bg5 Bg7
7. Bb5+ Bd7 8. Qe2
{ This is one of the most popular White's sidelines. The first player wants to castle on the queenside quickly and go for e5. }
8... a6 { Forcing the trade. } 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. O-O-O Rc8
{ Our intentions are clear, but White cannot prevent them. } 11. f4 Rxc3
{ 11...O-O  is perfectly playable, but can anyone resist the temptation of sacrificing this way? }
12. bxc3 Qc7 { Pointing towards c3. } 13. Qf3
{ A very logical move, defending the pawn and improving the queen's position. }
13... O-O 14. h4 { Trying to create trouble on the kingside. } 14... h5
{ As White's light-squared bishop is gone, we can make this move without hesitation. }
15. Nb3 { Preempting Black's threats. } 15... Rc8 16. Rh3 b5
{ Our attack flows while White, despite the extra exchange, is limited to defend. }
