1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White indicates they want to go for d4 and the Open Sicilian. } 2... d6
{ Black's most popular move at the top level because of its flexibility, and definitely the move we want to play if we intend to go into a Dragon setup. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Preparing to fianchetto our pride and joy - the Dragon bishop. } 6. Bg5 Bg7
7. Qd2 { An aggressive attempt by White. } 7... h6
{ We force White to go to h4 as  8.Be3  would be directly met by  8...Ng4  . }
8. Bh4
{ The inclusion of these moves makes White's attack on the kingside practically nonexistent. }
8... Nc6 9. Nb3 Be6 10. O-O-O O-O
{ We can continue our typical plans on the queenside, but what can White do? It's not clear to me at all! Let's see a possible continuation. }
11. Kb1 { Slightly improving the king's position. } 11... a5
{ Encouraging White to play a4, which would weaken the king's home. } 12. a4
Rc8 { As so often, the rook belongs on the c-file. } 13. Bb5 Nd7
{ Clearing the long diagonal at the same time that we bring the knight to the c5 square. }
14. f4 Na7
{ This move's idea is not only to threaten to grab the bishop b5. If White retreats it, we can take on c3 with the bishop without complexes, weakening the queenside. }
15. Nd4 Nxb5 16. Ndxb5 Nc5
{ Followed by ...Bc4 or even ...Qe8, with the idea of playing ...Nxa4 next and have great attacking chances. }
