[White "Test Your Understanding"]
[Black "Strategy Exercise #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r3k1/1pq1ppb1/p2pbnp1/7p/2rBP3/1NN1QP1P/PPP3P1/1K1RR3 w - - 0 19"]
[SetUp "1"]

19. Qd3
{ Identify White's weak points and try to recall Black's typical plan. } 19...
b5
{ Of course. Going for queenside expansion, harassing the knight on c3, which is so often the key defender of White's queenside. If it ever moves, we crash through on c2. }
20. e5
{ Of course White won't sit back and let you roll over them without a fight. }
20... Bf5 21. Qe2 Nd5
{ This is a picturesque position of how Sicilian attacks often start. Every piece is actively positioned to target White's king while Black's king is safe. If White doesn't break through in the center, they will lose quickly. }
22. exd6 Nxc3+ 23. bxc3 exd6 24. Bxg7 Kxg7
{ Black had to part with the dark-squared bishop and the c3-knight, both of which were good defenders of the kingside. Even after the simplifications, we retain some pressure and White has to play more accurately to survive. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Test Your Understanding"]
[Black "Strategy Exercise #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/pp3p2/2npbnp1/4p2p/4P3/1NN1BP2/PPP1B1PP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White has just castled kingside. Often that is our cue that we can be a bit more liberal on the kingside. What is the thematic plan here? }
10... h4
{ Advancing Harry one step further and making way for ...Nh5, honing in on the kingside dark squares. }
11. h3 Nh5
{ The knight on g3 will be a big thorn for White to have to play around. The position takes on a somewhat more positional nature than usual. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Test Your Understanding"]
[Black "Strategy Exercise #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3qk2r/pp1bppb1/3p1np1/7p/2rNP3/2N1BP1P/PPPQ2P1/1K1R3R b k - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We've seen this plan before, beginning with a very versatile move. } 14... h4
{ Facilitating the development of our rook, or sometimes the knight. We'd rather activate this way than commit to ...O-O and allow White an easy attack with g4. }
15. Rhe1 Rh5
{ The rook can play along the 4th rank. Often, it is satisfied on this specific square for quite some time while we prepare our typical pawn storm starting with ...b5 since the rook now supports this advance! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Test Your Understanding"]
[Black "Strategy Exercise #4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/1pq1ppb1/p2p1np1/7p/P3P3/1BN1BP2/1PPQ2PP/R3K2R b KQ - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We need to finish developing, but what's the best method? } 13... Be6
{ The most natural square, offering a trade for White's active bishop on b3. Sometimes developing quickly is more important than retaining an ideal structure. }
14. Bxe6 fxe6
{ Despite an ugly pawn structure, it's not easy to attack. In fact, Black seems to have better play with half-open files for the rooks. Next, the knight comes to d7 and plays on the dark squares. }
*

