[Black "Tactic #5: Svenn, M. vs. Berg, E. Swedish Ch. 2005"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2q1k3/pp2ppb1/3p2p1/r2P4/2r4p/3Q1P1P/PPP2BP1/1K1RR3 b - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black has arranged his attacking forces optimally while White has not achieved much in the center. This spells doom. }
22... Bxb2 { Luring the king to b2, else White is busted anyway. } 23. Kxb2
Rxc2+ 24. Kb1
{ 24.Qxc2  Rxa2+  25.Kxa2  Qxc2+  and Black will be up too many pawns. } 24...
Rxf2
{ The white king is not long for this world, but we're not even down material. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Test Your Understanding"]
[Black "Tactic #6: Pham, Minh Hoang vs. Postny, E. Champion's Challenge, 2006"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rq1rk1/pp1bppb1/3p1np1/4n2p/3NP3/1BN1BP1P/PPP1Q1P1/2KR3R b - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What is the most promising continuation for Black? } 13... Rxc3
{ An all too thematic tactic in these positions when c3 is defended only by a pawn. Of course, calculation is required to determine if there's a good follow-up. }
14. bxc3 Qa5 { White needs to pinpoint accuracy just to survive. } 15. f4
{ This is too much, disregarding Black's initiative and allowing the knight from f6 into the attack. }
15... Nxe4 16. fxe5 Qa3+ 17. Kb1 Nxc3+
{ Black is winning the queen and goes up too much material. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Test Your Understanding"]
[Black "Tactic #7 (Composed)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pp1bppb1/3p1npp/8/2BQP3/2N4P/PPPB1PP1/R3R1K1 b - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Oftentimes White's queen ends up in line with our bishop and most of the time, they remove it from the x-ray. Other times they allow us a combination that can lead to positional or material gains. How to best proceed here? }
12... Ng4
{ Here, the e5-square is a useful pivotal point for the knight, which wins us some tempi. }
13. Qd3 Ne5 14. Qe2 Nxc4 15. Qxc4 Rc8 16. Qd3 a6
{ We have the bishop pair with a great queenside initiative. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
