[Black "Simon's Spicy Dragon - Instructions"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Divis has broken new ground in the Dragon with the new variation involving ...Bh6, which is the topic of the course. However, our esteemed presenter, Simon Williams has a wealth of knowledge to share from his games played in the Classical Dragon.   A lot of the attacking motifs do cross over, and especially the necessity to always stay on your toes and calculate your way through sticky situations, and to convert your dynamic advantages.   So, Simon has collected some of his games in the Dragon for you to play along with and learn from. In the video, he asks you to pause at key moments to calculate the best continuation. The Chessable team has also transformed these exercises into interactive puzzles for you to review again and again.   We hope you enjoy Simon's Spicy Dragon! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Simon's Spicy Dragon"]
[Black "Vaibhav, S. vs. Williams, S. Big Slick, London, 2011 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/pp1bppbp/3p1np1/q3n2P/3NP1P1/2N1BP2/PPPQ4/2KR1B1R w - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13. Kb1
{ Simon had just playted ...Qa5, and his opponent continued Nb3, but if instead, the natural Kb1 was played, there's an incredibly messy variation that Black can uncork. Can you navigate the chaos? }
13... Nxf3
{ Taking the anchor pawn of White's structure. Now the g- and e- pawns will fall like dominos. }
14. Nxf3 Rxc3 15. Qxc3 { Black is a whole rook down! } 15... Qxc3 16. bxc3 Bxg4
{ Black begins to gobble the pawns. } 17. Bg2 Nxe4
{ the c-pawn will fall next and this is incredibly unclear. Not to mention, White's attack is stopped in its tracks. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Simon's Spicy Dragon"]
[Black "Vaibhav, S. vs. Williams, S. Big Slick, London, 2011 #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/ppqbppbp/3p1np1/4n2P/4P1P1/1NN1BP2/PPPQ4/2KR1B1R w - - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14. Be2
{ White had to take a time out to defend the f-pawn, giving Black a chance to create some counterplay of his own. What was Simon's choice? }
14... b5
{ Of course! Rolling ahead with the minority attack. The next moves should be ...b4 and ...a5 with pressure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Simon's Spicy Dragon"]
